commit_message:
Don't write python bytecode while testing

This patch was based on the Nova patch:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121044

This should reduce the number of times you need to completely delete
your tox dir because you have stale pyc files around.

In Ironic we have hit this problem a number of times, migrating to
oslo.message was a big one that caused a lot of confusion.

Closes-Bug: #1368661
Change-Id: I7dda3ad879beff1e494a36144c941a847177c2ef

commit_message:
Moves cinder tests to cidner_volues script

As the installation of cinder volumes section is separated to another
node (compute node for now) which may not be the same node as the
node running controller side of cinder's services, the tests should
also be moved to the appropriate location.

Change-Id: I2c2e6e64807e026783881197d62243b4751f7f41

commit_message:
Remova the nova cherry-pick

It has merged and the cherry-pick no fails (causing CI to fail).

Also ignore errors from the other cherry-pick so it doesn't call
failures if it fails.

Change-Id: Ic51d4995a68af17caeacbf1668db1bcf752d0f46

commit_message:
Adds hint about filter placement to extension docs

Since a filter cannot be the last entry in a pipeline it makes sense to
call that out in the extension documentation.

Change-Id: Idf73bdb6d6d237cbf9d108f67eeb8020caeaa364
Related-Bug: #1363932

commit_message:
Making KvsInheritanceTests use backend KVS

The KvsInheritanceTests does not use backend
KVS as identity driver. This patch fix this
by setting it in the config_overrides method.

Change-Id: I45e80e18d7dbcd027493755a8bd30c3fc7e09638
Closes-Bug: 1364618

commit_message:
Fix keystone auth parameter to neutron conf

Devstack set auth_uri to  metadata_agent.ini.
But auth_uri is wrong parameter for metadate_agent.

This is regression caused by https://review.openstack.org/#/c/94545/

Change-Id: I3dcf1d619b5d204937f072b3fbb9966069793680
Closes-bug: #1364684

[{'created': '2014-09-10 11:49:30.000000000', 'message': 'Fix the warning message of CINDER_MULTI_LVM_BACKEND

CINDER_MULTI_LVM_BACKEND is marked as deprecated and we recommend
to use CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS instead now. However current warning
message shows that CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS will be removed.
This patch fixes the message.

Change-Id: I3ca25e4273c3abebce1cfefe1ae4af622b71e993
'}]
commit_message:
Fix the warning message of CINDER_MULTI_LVM_BACKEND

CINDER_MULTI_LVM_BACKEND is marked as deprecated and we recommend
to use CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS instead now. However current warning
message shows that CINDER_ENABLED_BACKENDS will be removed.
This patch fixes the message.

Change-Id: I3ca25e4273c3abebce1cfefe1ae4af622b71e993

[{'created': '2014-09-10 22:13:58.000000000', 'message': "check-sanity skip checking q-fwaas and q-l3

FWaaS is running as a service plugin in neutron-server and doesn't have
any dedicated process. When Neutron is deployed with VPNaaS it's running
instead of l3-agent with the same capabilites as L3 agent has. Thus
checking whether processes for these services are running is not
necessary.

Change-Id: I8f438cfccc84be801d4064bdb564a95c6621bf55
(cherry picked from commit 49883a0270ede3dfdfe15bde2930c9df9bdc8c7f)
"}]
commit_message:
check-sanity skip checking q-fwaas and q-l3

FWaaS is running as a service plugin in neutron-server and doesn't have
any dedicated process. When Neutron is deployed with VPNaaS it's running
instead of l3-agent with the same capabilites as L3 agent has. Thus
checking whether processes for these services are running is not
necessary.

Change-Id: I8f438cfccc84be801d4064bdb564a95c6621bf55
(cherry picked from commit 49883a0270ede3dfdfe15bde2930c9df9bdc8c7f)

commit_message:
ofagent: Switch to IptablesFirewallDriver

The latest version of ofagent
(ie. after blueprint ofagent-port-monitor)
follows IptablesFirewallDriver naming scheme.

Closes-Bug: #1364731
Related: blueprint ofagent-port-monitor
Change-Id: I690aab71b1cb222ffb8b458c90740ba623b0b37e

commit_message:
delete python bytecode before every test run

Bring over the cleaning line from run_tests.sh for the pyc files to
all the tox runs.

This should eliminate the need to clean -x -i to kill pyc files in
your local directory to get tests to pass.

Related-Bug: #1368661

Change-Id: I00ee418eea2d82031bb510b09e63e2ec87fb1b09

commit_message:
Update to latest oslo.vmware

* Fix seek and tell in BlockingQueue
* Add DuplicateName exception
* Add details property to VMwareDriverException
* Enable oslo.i18n for oslo.vmware
* Add API to enable calling module to register an exception
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add docs target and generate api docs
* Updated from global requirements
* Work toward Python 3.4 support and testing
* warn against sorting requirements
* Add exception for TaskInProgress
* Updated from global requirements
* Refactoring to reduce noise in log files
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add missing session parameter to get_summary
* Updated from global requirements
* Switch off caching to prevent cache poisoning by local attacker
* Support for copying streamOptimized disk to file
* Add support for the DatastoreURL object
* Add methods to the Datastore objects
* Imported Translations from Transifex
* Add Pylint testenv environment

commit_message:
correct inverted subtraction in quota check

From a user reported bug: we were doing the subtraction backwards
here, causing int overflow, causing all kinds of invalid. Instead
actually subtract the smaller number from the bigger number.

Change-Id: I7c099df5e31aa25b8be65c570e2e0b8a3e93c277
Closes-Bug: #1363324

Corrected configuration value request example

When coding the set configuration value API, it became clear that a
different request body would be beneficial. This commit updates the spec
with the changes.

commit_message:
Default value of 'global/namenode_opt_maxnewsize' should be 200m

    Default value for HDP plugin configuration property
    'global/namenode_opt_maxnewsize' should be changed
    from 640m to 200m.

Change-Id: Ib7ebe383ccacf0b11a038d7a6a2be6ebff2ee115
Closes-Bug: 1291029

A few of the LDAP searches performed in the identity and assignment
LDAP drivers do not specify the list of attributes to return, which
causes all attributes present in the LDAP entry to be returned.  We
attempt to convery these values from utf8 to unicode, which fails
when we encounter a binary value.  This patch addresses this problem
in two ways.

The first is to only request the attributes that we actually need
returned from the LDAP server.  This avoids potential binary values
that we do not even need to be concerned with.

The second thing this patch does is to make our conversion code
more tolerant by ignoring attributes that contain binary values.  If
a binary value is present, we simply skip over that attribute in
the conversion and log a debug message.  We should not be encounting
binary values in a typical Keystone deployment, but this gives us
some protection just in case we do encounter a binary value.

        keystone/identity/backends/ldap.py

commit_message:
Avoid conversion of binary LDAP values

A few of the LDAP searches performed in the identity and assignment
LDAP drivers do not specify the list of attributes to return, which
causes all attributes present in the LDAP entry to be returned.  We
attempt to convery these values from utf8 to unicode, which fails
when we encounter a binary value.  This patch addresses this problem
in two ways.

The first is to only request the attributes that we actually need
returned from the LDAP server.  This avoids potential binary values
that we do not even need to be concerned with.

The second thing this patch does is to make our conversion code
more tolerant by ignoring attributes that contain binary values.  If
a binary value is present, we simply skip over that attribute in
the conversion and log a debug message.  We should not be encounting
binary values in a typical Keystone deployment, but this gives us
some protection just in case we do encounter a binary value.

Conflicts:
        keystone/assignment/backends/ldap.py
        keystone/identity/backends/ldap.py

Closes-bug: #1355489
Change-Id: I62325ab9c75bac67cca329fb7bd3c74aea7d2867
(cherry picked from commit 940551c6bdd1477574c1dee165efe75366343bd7)

commit_message:
Add vmedia boot support for deploy-ironic element

deploy-ironic element currently retrieves token over tftp and
expects BOOT_IP_ADDRESS to be set.  This commit adds support for
retrieving token file from virtual media if node booted from
virtual media. Also corrects the issue for BOOT_IP_ADDRESS not set
for virtual media boot.

Change-Id: I3d5f1779b9b17842360860c7778baa01db1e1a52
Closes-Bug: #1356339

Fix 'simple_flat_node_deletion' test

In the simple cluster configuration it is impossible
to remove a single controller now. So let's delete
a compute node instead.

(cherry picked from commit cc76281c797bfc2a447babd23782a94206dcefcb)

commit_message:
Fix run workflow in case task state == ERROR

 * If task has state 'ERROR' then we should check
   on-error property and schedule next tasks.
   Otherwise Mistral doesn't schedule any task if
   task failed.

Change-Id: Ib55509e2ca7f9db22bb46ceb930f1ead8a763c78

Another concern for me is why we should add some external libs to support HA for this? Can we change processing algorithm in such a way that it would not be required? I would prefer so implement such solution instead of complicated master-slave configuration with some external tool to support it.'}, {'account_id': 2813, 'date': '2014-06-04 10:01:19.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 4:

@Alexei:

I don't think, we need UpgradeImpact, this is a 'new' implementation to evaluate alarms, you can continue to use the old one.

If you use this implementation, they are nothing to do about HA, they are no master/slave stuffs here, taskflow dispatchs alarm evaluation across nodes, if a node fail/die taskflow will reschedule the failed evaluation of the alarm an other nodes. taskflow use zookeeper to ensure that.

The node that make the alarms dispatch continues to use the current rpc implementation to elect the master node, and at the end we have planned to move out the master node election from ceilometer by using 'tooz' (that can use zookeeper too)."}, {'account_id': 7763, 'date': '2014-06-04 11:09:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: -Code-Review

uses the same basic idea: a master node keeps track of the alarms to be

commit_message:
Add an alarm service based on taskflow

In the long term, it could be a replacement for the PartitionedAlarmService. It
uses the same basic idea: a master node keeps track of the alarms to be
evaluated, but instead of distributing a slice of the alarms to each node, it
just maintains a pool from which the other nodes can pick some work. This pool
is managed by taskflow, for instance by using a multi-node Zookeeper
configuration.

The election of the master node works as in the PartitionCoordinator.

In this service, the nodes are not "passive" (they do not wait for work to be
given to them); they are "active" (they ask for work when they have nothing
more to do).

Thanks to Florent Flament for his help with the tests.

Co-Authored-By: Florent Flament <florent.flament@cloudwatt.com>
Change-Id: I367be0d1337a3a8683519342d18cd628e7510ddc

commit_message:
Fix indent in output of cinder quota-usage tenantID

WIthout this change:

$ cinder quota-usage tenantID
            +-----------+--------+----------+-------+
...

With this change:

$ cinder quota-usage tenantID
+-----------+--------+----------+-------+
...

commit_message:
shared policy shouldn't have unshared rules

A shared firewall policy should always have shared rules. So the following
cases should not be allowed:
1.Create shared policy with unshared rules
2.Update policy shared=True when it has unshared rules
3.Update policy with shared=True and unshared rules
4.Update shared policy with unshared rules

Change-Id: I3d71899c328d3fefa96c1f99d6ba706160e445cc
Closes-bug: 1334981

commit_message:
Allow to specify policy by name in firewall-update

Currently only firewall policy ids are supported in firewall-update,
this change allows to use firewall policy names in firewall-update:

  neutron firewall-update my-firewall --policy my-new-policy

DocImpact
Change-Id: I84ad97fc7f1f2e81cad98497d4d983606fa03077

commit_message:
Clean-up shell run and run_subcommand methods

Remove else branch of try-catch block since
it is never executed.

Get rid of passing result to shell clean-up function
since it is not used.

Change-Id: I9360d1e27fc203672ba0511b58172f5c776bdfb6

In verbose mode, iso8601 package produces the following useless debug
messages:

DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'2014' for 'year' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'09' for 'monthdash' with default 1
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got 9 for 'month' with default 9
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'14' for 'daydash' with default 1
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got 14 for 'day' with default 14
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'16' for 'hour' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'31' for 'minute' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'23' for 'second' with default None

This change silences them.

Change-Id: Ibd0c5bb48b1ab86aaee2c8cb4f27b7e5fa8b4bef
"}]
commit_message:
Silence iso8601 debug messages in verbose mode

In verbose mode, iso8601 package produces the following useless debug
messages:

DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'2014' for 'year' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'09' for 'monthdash' with default 1
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got 9 for 'month' with default 9
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'14' for 'daydash' with default 1
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got 14 for 'day' with default 14
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'16' for 'hour' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'31' for 'minute' with default None
DEBUG: iso8601.iso8601 Got u'23' for 'second' with default None

This change silences them.

Change-Id: Ibd0c5bb48b1ab86aaee2c8cb4f27b7e5fa8b4bef

In 2bc74e66d90b6fae3c5ca8f79f99e75169da644f we recently changed
the HostState.consume_from_instance method parameters to include a
context. This patch updates the relevate baremetal/ironic host state
classes to do likewise.

This fixes a critical TypeError that occurs when trying to use
Ironic or Nova Baremetal otherwise.

Closes-bug: #1369151
'}]
commit_message:
Correct baremetal/ironic consume_from_instance...

In 2bc74e66d90b6fae3c5ca8f79f99e75169da644f we recently changed
the HostState.consume_from_instance method parameters to include a
context. This patch updates the relevate baremetal/ironic host state
classes to do likewise.

This fixes a critical TypeError that occurs when trying to use
Ironic or Nova Baremetal otherwise.

Change-Id: I46eebce19603cb4c4a934b1647ff6433d75799ad
Closes-bug: #1369151

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:48:43.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Block sqlalchemy migrate 0.9.2 as it breaks all of nova

This is breaking nova unit tests

Closes-Bug: #1368391
(cherry picked from commit 9c2d6f21854bc79f03095163b8133a9fec68f9f2)

Change-Id: Ic82d787e41f7b6d6153d3c6b19902cc11a1c43bb

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-16 11:51:59.000000000', 'message': 'Add validate alarm_actions schema in alarm API

Currently, alarm API does not validate schema in alarm_actions.
When invalid schema is specified, error occurs later in alarm notifier.
Schema should be validated in advance in API.

Supported schemata will be defined in config. Instead, getting the schemata
from entry_points.txt seems to be possible, but it is not a good idea from
following reason: Schema in entry_points.txt are used by alarm-notifier,
whereas schema check needs to be done in API.
Since alarm-notifier and API may running on different host, the file might
differ as well.

Change-Id: I3b28cfe36c460daead2945ba3577fbc1274f9d91
Closes-bug: #1342673

commit_message:
Add validate alarm_actions schema in alarm API

Currently, alarm API does not validate schema in alarm_actions.
When invalid schema is specified, error occurs later in alarm notifier.
Schema should be validated in advance in API.

Change-Id: I3b28cfe36c460daead2945ba3577fbc1274f9d91
Closes-bug: #1342673

commit_message:
Add unit-test assert to check dict is superset of dict

Several VPN unit tests need the ability to check that an expected
dict is found in the actual dict output (and that other elements are
ignored - like auth tokens).

Since this will be of use to other components, adding this to the
base test case.

Note: There is a similar assertDictContainsSubset(), however, it is
not supported in 2.6 and has been deprecated in 3.2. A different, and
hopefully clearer, name is used for this method.

Change-Id: I8becf9cfad966874f8463a9c835331f2f17d2ead
Closes-Bug: 1366797

commit_message:
Fix 'simple_flat_node_deletion' test

In the simple cluster configuration it is impossible
to remove a single controller now. So let's delete
a compute node instead.

Change-Id: I902200fbbd7096f4039b18a0a59fc2eab692c0cf
Closes-bug: #1368820

commit_message:
Add OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent resource

This patch adds a SoftwareComponent resource for defining
configurations for a software component's different lifecycle
actions.

The current patch only adds the basic code for the resource and
initial test code. A subsequent patch in this chain will add more
validation (beyond basic property schema validation), e.g. to make
sure that not more than one config is defined for one lifecycle
action.

Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

Change-Id: Idd9de7edf3bab99f26911a0d018a1d433381deb4

commit_message:
Enabled Cisco ML2 driver to use new upstream ncclient

The code is still able to handle the old, custom ncclient that
we used before. It uses the different function signatures
for the ncclient's connect() function to detect which version
is installed.

Change-Id: I09d81b424d86f4cd35ca048507f06471246b91d8
Closes-Bug: 1352635

commit_message:
Add support for token validation

Support for both token validation methods, the one that returns a set of
permissions and one that simply returns a True/False based on whether
the token is valid.

Change-Id: Ib1066a733ed396f05c0f354b93b0a697a0a6acc1
Closes-Bug: #1313264

- gate-qa-specs-docs http://docs-draft.openstack.org/52/118352/2/check/gate-qa-specs-docs/a1ed5c6/doc/build/html/ : SUCCESS in 1m 20s'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2014-09-05 18:08:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

I think we should not mix the short term goal of making sure tearDownClass is always called from the goal of having a "cleaner" breakdown of the setup code and optimal skipping. Especially since many have spoken of getting rid of setUpClass in favor of fixtures as a future goal. So I actually like the second POC better. With the first one you don't have to put @safe_setup in the setUpClass of each new test class, but you do have to figure out in which of the new helper methods the setup code should go. There could be a hacking test that makes sure setUpClass always has the decorator. It is a shame the test runners do not support the option of putting try/except around calls to setUpClass themselves.'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:24:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

I agree splitting the setup in multiple methods to optimize it is not as urgent as making sure fixtures are safe. Only I thought it might be worth doing the two things in one go. Probably not worth it as it will make reviews more complex. I'll move this part to alternatives.

Besides that we still need to change both setup and teardown methods, as ensuring teardown is always called is not enough.

For the teardown I'm quite keen on factoring up the credentials cleanup into the base class as in my code example, as with the pre-provisioned accounts it's vital that credentials are released."}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:32:32.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 1192, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:47:15.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-05 20:59:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

(3 comments)

Looks good. just some nit'}, {'account_id': 8576, 'date': '2014-09-11 09:26:19.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

I don't know if this is a concern even, or a cause for -1:
What about failures in setUp, are they taken care of by tearDown?
Anyway, since our tests will start having "setup_class" instead of seUpClass, maybe we could give the same treatment to setUp/tearDown so they have the same naming structure, and the same logic?'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-09-11 12:07:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

(3 comments)'}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-09-11 12:12:11.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 3:

Yair, test level resources are handled via addCleanup, they don't rely on tearDown for their cleanup. So this shouldn't be a concern. 
Even though having set_up_class and tear_down_class is needed for what we want to do in tempest, I'm not a big fan of the idea - it probably means that we're not using the framework the way it was designed to be used; so I'd like to avoid doing that for test level fixture unless it's really needed."}, {'account_id': 1921, 'date': '2014-09-11 12:25:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-11 12:32:05.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4: Verified+1

commit_message:
Enhance SoftwareComponent property validation

This patch enhances the property validation for
OS::Heat::SoftwareComponent beyond what is done with property schema
validation. This allows for reporting additional validation errors
to users.

Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

Change-Id: I512c74341d9271bc07f78149d45d662484241ada

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-08 15:48:19.000000000', 'message': "Enable SoftwareDeployment for SoftwareComponent

This patch enables the existing SoftwareDeployment resource to cope
with the new SoftwareComponent resource, i.e. allow for associating a
SoftwareComponent resource to a server via a SoftwareDeployment.

Main changes are:
(1) In case of a SoftwareComponent resource, look at the 'actions'
    lists of single configs to see when the the SoftwareDeployment
    should act (instead of looking at its own 'actions' property).
(2) Make sure that either the 'config' (in case of SoftwareConfig) or
    the 'configs' (in case of SoftwareComponent) property is copied
    to the derived software config that will be read by in-instance
    tools.

Note: to activate correct processing on a SoftwareComponent data on
an instance, an update to the os-collect-config plug-in
(55-heat-config) in the heat-templates repository is required. That
updated will be provided as a patch to heat-templates.

Change-Id: I45d4d373babe0fff9b109cba97ce7ebcb90562df

with the new SoftwareComponent resource, i.e. allow for associating a
SoftwareComponent resource to a server via a SoftwareDeployment.

Main changes are:
(1) In case of a SoftwareComponent resource, look at the 'actions'
    lists of single configs to see when the the SoftwareDeployment
    should act (instead of looking at its own 'actions' property).
(2) Make sure that either the 'config' (in case of SoftwareConfig) or
    the 'configs' (in case of SoftwareComponent) property is copied
    to the derived software config that will be read by in-instance
    tools.

Note: to activate correct processing on a SoftwareComponent data on
an instance, an update to the os-collect-config plug-in
(55-heat-config) in the heat-templates repository is required. That
updated will be provided as a patch to heat-templates.

Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

Note: to activate correct processing of SoftwareComponent data on

55-heat-config will be implemented and posted to the heat-templates

'group' property of 'component'.

derive the configuration to be applied based on the current resource
action and then invoke the appropriate configuration hook.

commit_message:
Enable SoftwareDeployment for SoftwareComponent

This patch enables the existing SoftwareDeployment resource to cope
with the new SoftwareComponent resource, i.e. allow for associating a
SoftwareComponent resource to a server via a SoftwareDeployment.

In case of a SoftwareComponent resource, the SoftwareDeployment
resource will act at each resource action and create a derived
config to be passed to in-instances tools (instead of looking at its
own 'actions' property).

Note: to activate correct processing of SoftwareComponent data on
an instance, an additional os-collect-config plug-in similar to
55-heat-config will be implemented and posted to the heat-templates
repository. 55-heat-config will ignore configuration data with a
'group' property of 'component'.
The new in-instance hook will analyze component configurations,
derive the configuration to be applied based on the current resource
action and then invoke the appropriate configuration hook.

Implements: partial-blueprint action-aware-sw-config

Change-Id: I45d4d373babe0fff9b109cba97ce7ebcb90562df

commit_message:
Corrected dash.can_access call to take context

horizon_main_nav makes a call to dash.can_access which should take
context but was being passed the request, this patch corrects that.
Unit test added to prevent regression, and fix added to RbacHorizonTests
to clean up changes to Cats and Dogs test dashboards, as it was
affecting any test that followed.

Change-Id: I46d9880ba3ac46c23a8253a4afcf2c169d6f4dc8
Closes-Bug: 1368673

commit_message:
Order tenants in tenant switch list

Currently tenants are displayed in random order in tenant switch list.
This change display them ordered.

Closes-Bug: #1368757
Change-Id: Ifc49b90b98d69254bf5e05206a334981c507a920

commit_message:
Adding django kwargs to login and logout views

The django.contrib.auth.views login and logout views take usefull parameters
which where dropped by the openstack_auth.views methods.

Added a TOKEN_TIMEOUT_MARGIN which allows to check token expiration minus a
time margin in seconds. This is usefull if you know a process will take a
certain time, you want to have your token still valid all this time (e.g. the
time it can take to render a view).

This patch is required for https://review.openstack.org/88220

Change-Id: I7508c40d6f1eaa2bf1eef5cc762052b15d6d9273
Closes-Bug: 1308918

commit_message:
Switch to xstatic-bootstrap-datepicker

This points to datepicker 1.3.1 in xstatic.
Also fixes a couple of minor bugs in forms with
the new datepicker. The datepicker patch is:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/116866/

Change-Id: I0a8cb7a16e50addbbdb10df8bdd4be427937bd81
Closes-Bug: 1361666

commit_message:
Installation Guide XML IDs change

Changing the XML IDs of several chapters in the installation
guide for consistency, and to match the section title, which
follows conventions. Minor subjective edits also included.

Change-Id: Id33aa27ef2027ac13f129c3bae150492b4bbfa13
backport:none
Implements: blueprint installation-guide-improvements
Co-Authored-By: Matt Kassawara <mkassawara@gmail.com>

To run the tempest unit tests with coverage enabled the coverage

commit_message:
Fix tox coverage job

To run the tempest unit tests with coverage enabled the coverage
module needs to be installed. This requirement is properly listed in
test-requirements.txt, however the coverage job definition wasn't
installing coverage. This commit fixes this oversight by adding the
test-requirements file as a dependency for the job.

Change-Id: Ic443c6c4a3166e6b198cbe2af0a77ff2f0a38e83

/etc/sysctl.conf instead (and reload file with sysctl -p).

Change-Id: Icf0191774e0d1b8f65345cc980460ec8f86d7153
'}]
commit_message:
labs: make sysctl configuration survive reboots

Sysctl configuration set with "sysctl -w" does not survive reboots. Edit
/etc/sysctl.conf instead (and reload file with sysctl -p).

Change-Id: Icf0191774e0d1b8f65345cc980460ec8f86d7153

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-12 20:50:38.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Run post-configure.d/15-apache2 earlier

The certs this scripts creates are needed by 14-horizon so run them in
the correct order.

Change-Id: I84d1d49892828cef8678cd2381134716dd922849
Closes-Bug: #1368465

[{'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:08:49.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 1.'}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:30:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

(1 comment)

This seems like a good idea but the fact that manager is being passed to some plugins that then don't use it is vaguely annoying. Is it worth making it an optional parameter?

Or is it better to have it in place to give a clear signal of the future opportunities?

The -1 is because of the swp file."}, {'account_id': 11564, 'date': '2014-09-12 13:31:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review-1

Forgot to give the actual vote, see previous comments.'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-12 14:09:38.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Oops, don't know how that swp file got there! :)

Regarding the optional parameter. I did it this way to be consistent in the way pollster plugins get access to the manager - they get it passed as a parameter to get_samples function.

The only one that actually calls the discover() functions is the manager itself, so I don't know if we gain anything by making it an optional parameter.

It could also be used for some other heavyweight things to be shared among discoveries in the future, if it's necessary."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:13:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Verified-1

commit_message:
Use central agent manager's keystone token in discoveries

Currently, EndpointDiscovery creates its own keystone client.
This patch passes an agent-manager reference into the discoveries,
enabling them to reuse the manager's keystone client and possibly
other things in the future.

Change-Id: I9875f15c4be25c2ac125458caa9a09927afdf3b2
Closes-bug: #1368125

in a special sub-shell to use other credentials.

commit_message:
Fix preparation of aki/ari/ami images on Ubuntu

The boto tests currently don't run because euca-bundle-image fails on
Ubuntu; e.g.

---
 ++ euca-bundle-image -r x86_64 \
  -i /opt/stack/new/devstack/files/images/cirros-0.3.2-x86_64-uec/cirros-0.3.2-x86_64-vmlinuz \
  --kernel true \
  -d /opt/stack/new/devstack/files/images/s3-materials/cirros-0.3.2

 euca-bundle-image: error: No such file or directory: /opt/stack/new/devstack/files/images/s3-materials/cirros-0.3.2
---

I noticed this in debugging why Fedora tests are running slower.  I
think that the version of euca-bundle-image in Fedora must create the
directory if it doesn't exist, while the Ubuntu one fails.

I also think this doesn't get caught by errexit because it's running
in a special sub-shell to use other credentials.

Change-Id: I79125e956088353aa76a3f7d6d81af1e4f6a27d4

'}, {'created': '2014-09-09 17:15:24.000000000', 'message': 'Add a check for SQLite transactional state

When we intercept SQLite transactions for BEGIN, check
a marker that we place there to indicate BEGIN has
already been called, which we then remove on commit or
rollback.  This is to resolve the issue of the fact
that we currently use the StaticPool implementation

commit_message:
Add a check for SQLite transactional state

When we intercept SQLite transactions for BEGIN, check
a marker that we place there to indicate BEGIN has
already been called, which we then remove on commit or
rollback.  This is to resolve the issue of the fact
that we currently use the StaticPool implementation
with SQLite, which shares a single SQLite connection
for all requests; any API method which makes use
of multiple sessions at once (not a good idea, but
this is prevalent throughout nova, neutron) will
therefore share the same SQLite connection with
multiple SQLAlchemy Connection wrappers that are not
aware of the existing state.  While this practice
should be corrected, for now the marker, which is
local to the SQLite connection as stored by the
pool, will track when BEGIN is safe to call, or
has already been called.

Change-Id: I70d44104412bd99d8c7713eb6cd9ff0f80c5da34
Closes-Bug: #1367354

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-02-11 12:07:52.000000000', 'message': 'Remove NotImplementedErrors from "virtual" methods

Raising a NotImplementedError in a method of a base class
makes it impossible to use super() with it and do multiple
inheritance properly. Those methods should instead simply
return some default "empty" value, so that the methods in
the subclasses can still call them, if that's where they
fall in the MRO.

Change-Id: I581391e87dc58f0f76adea3dbf90cef173d3daef
Closes-bug: 1278825
'}, {'created': '2014-03-03 08:40:41.000000000', 'message': 'Remove NotImplementedErrors from "virtual" methods

Raising a NotImplementedError in a method of a base class
makes it impossible to use super() with it and do multiple
inheritance properly. Those methods should instead simply
return some default "empty" value, so that the methods in
the subclasses can still call them, if that's where they

commit_message:
Remove NotImplementedErrors from "virtual" methods

Raising a NotImplementedError in a method of a base class
makes it impossible to use super() with it and do multiple
inheritance properly. Those methods should instead simply
return some default "empty" value, so that the methods in
the subclasses can still call them, if that's where they
fall in the MRO.

Change-Id: I581391e87dc58f0f76adea3dbf90cef173d3daef
Closes-bug: 1278825

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:25:03.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add test to compare security_group_info_for_devices with old rpc

security_group_info_for_devices is replacing the old
security_group_rules_for_devices rpc. The new one doesn't exhibit
exponential result size growth or execution time. This test
is to assert that the result size is small enough.

blueprint security-group-rules-for-devices-rpc-call-refactor

Change-Id: I7cb8f956a6a6c437e1c28ba69016c8083ad63caa

commit_message:
Use auth provider in official client manager

WIP - do not merge

Enforce using auth provider in the official client manager
so that the auth API version can be controlled for scenario
tests as well.

Partially implements: bp multi-keystone-api-version-tests

Change-Id: I860a23572bfab58043631e4ff7239deeacb6eff7

Official client based auth

Provide auth based on keystone official client with the
corresponding unit tests.

Multiversion auth part6

Partially implements: bp multi-keystone-api-version-tests

commit_message:
Improve OS::Compute::HostCapabilities description

The OS::Compute::HostCapabilities namespace should include more
information about how the properties are used by Nova.
Let admin's know that the ComputeCapabilitiesFilter needs to
be enabled.

Change-Id: Ib3232e560969462d3973606e138a96d1a5beb7de
Closes-bug: 1367860

commit_message:
Update neutron file permission

File permissions set in network cookbook should be set with 740 or
650 to avoid other users reading the secrete in configuration or
script files

Implements blueprint neutron-configured-files-permission
Change-Id: Id030ef2bc419d19127544876c7874f13aa37b6df

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:54:57.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Reduce unit test log level for notifications.

The current debug level of notifications causes unit test debug
files to be very large. This patch reduces the default log level
for notifications to INFO. This single change reduces the size
of the debug file by 20Mb (or 38%).

Change-Id: Idede6fd47d74705dd0fd62c009ebf7bba10f82ed
Closes-Bug: 1369180

commit_message:
Fix delete group cleans up role assignments with LDAP

When the LDAP assignment backend was used and a group was deleted,
the role assignments for the group were not getting cleaned up. The
role assignments for the group should have been removed along with the
group.

Change-Id: Ie506659c2b21e6a816335b00642fa4d0921a184d
Closes-Bug: #1366211

commit_message:
Update keystone file permission

File permissions set in identity cookbook should be set with 740 or
650 to avoid other users reading the secrete in configuration or
script files

Implements blueprint keystone-configured-files-permission
Change-Id: Ie571dcd71c8d1693a679ee073e58d421ab7af7c3

commit_message:
Cherry pick Neutron fix for enable_ipset breakage

setting update that recently broke Overcloud deployments.

See the neutron patch here:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121434/

commit_message:
Cherry pick Nova fix for Scheduler TypeError

This adds a cherry pick for a Nova fix that resolves
a TypeError in the Ironic and Nova Baremetal scheduler
host state classes:

https://review.openstack.org/#/c/121397/1

Also, removes the no-longer needed cherry pick for the
Nova Ironic extra_specs fix which has now landed.

Change-Id: I49a680b1373e16ce2887c97badfbaaa2f4232f69
Related-bug: #1369151

commit_message:
Big Switch: Check for 'id' in port before lookup

Check for the presence of the 'id' key before trying
to do a lookup based on the value. This is necessary
because a 'fields' param to get_port(s) may exclude
the 'id' field before the host_id lookup.

Closes-Bug: #1358668
Change-Id: If30567d5deaeabd2de6c6287fac7a81695a41cc5

[{'created': '2014-09-11 20:40:39.000000000', 'message': 'Workaround pypy bug on trusty when running tests

https://bitbucket.org/pypy/pypy/issue/1694/ affects zaqar when running
pypy tests on trusty slave nodes. We can work around that bug by setting
--jit off when running the pypy interpreter. Do this until the upstream
bug fix is backported into trusty.

Change-Id: Iebaa167e9e12bbc1017371929ca8c182bacc2aad
Related-Bug: 1368418
'}]
commit_message:
Workaround pypy bug on trusty when running tests

https://bitbucket.org/pypy/pypy/issue/1694/ affects zaqar when running
pypy tests on trusty slave nodes. We can work around that bug by setting
--jit off when running the pypy interpreter. Do this until the upstream
bug fix is backported into trusty.

Change-Id: Iebaa167e9e12bbc1017371929ca8c182bacc2aad
Related-Bug: 1368418

commit_message:
Skip info cache update in case instance is deleted

The network api is sometimes called for a deleted instance causing
info cache update to fail. An example of this is the compute manager
periodic task cleanup_running_deleted_instances() that tries to
shutdown deleted instances still running on a host.

Add a check in network_api.update_instance_cache_with_nw_info() that
will skip info cache update if the instance is deleted.

Change-Id: Ibcf2db92275c9860409793d469ed688e7024120b
Closes-Bug: #1282858

I feel a little ambivalent about overloading stderr like this; however, it occurs to me that there might be a small number of additional control lines that could be spat out to do things like changing the resulting file permissions (creating templated executable files, for example).

Reluctant to introduce too much magic into os-apply-config but on the other hand, this would reduce the need for splitting some file creation logic between o-a-c and o-r-c.'}, {'account_id': 1605, 'date': '2014-03-21 18:16:05.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

I share Jan's unease on the overloading of stderr in this way. Is it any cleaner to use a specifically defined non-zero return code? It could be tied to a FileEmptyException, which would be simply skipped in build_tree. Even then, still not sure about this.

However, there is a need for some mechanism like this. The use of os-refresh to handle this is not viable when / filesystem becomes read-only, as I've learnt from another review.

I would also like a method of skipping file creation when using regular templates, rather than just executable templates. The code could be changed to skip file creation when the content is empty, but might not always be desired."}, {'account_id': 4190, 'date': '2014-03-21 18:43:49.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

Can you please include more 'why' in the commit message? It's not clear when this is needed, which makes it hard to reason about its larger impact. We try hard to avoid the use of executable templates anyway, so this seems like its going to cause more of them to be used....

As far as readonly / goes, the pattern to work with that is to change the system config to use either (persistent state) /mnt/state/<orig path> or (derived state not required in early boot) /var/run/... either by using use-ephemeral/a symlink/a changed system config variable.

For instance, if this is in reference to the sysconfig example for rabbit, then since we restart procps to activate it, way to solve it using current tooling is to have a symlink from /etc/... to /var/run/procps/settings/var/run/procps/settings - and if there is nothing to write the file will exist and be empty, which isn't harmful."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-24 13:55:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: No score

It turns out my usecase doesn't need this patch, so I won't talk about it. I finished the feature anyway + put it up because Tom was asking about this capability too. Given two of us have thought about it already, I'd guess more people will ask, but if Tom's no longer interested either I could abandon for now.


I definitely prefer stderr to return code. There's a very limited space of return codes, so whichever number we pick it's more likely a script will return that code by accident than spit out the single string "DO_NOT_CREATE".

In fact that's so improbable we could use stdout, opening the possibility of using Mustache to spit out the special string. However as Mustache is intentionally logic-less, this would only fill the simplest usecases where we can put a marker parameter in the Heat template. We'd have to use exec-templates for anything more complex.


I expected a needs-doc -1 but wanted to iron out design issues first.

I definitely would not like split logic, IE creating the file then deleting it. Unnecessary work and the code would need big smelly marker comments.

I know nothing of read-only /.

Rob, I'm new, why are exec templates bad? Apart from ugly and potentially slow, buggy and unportable - maybe that's enough :)  Still, given Mustache's philosophy, the solution needs to be outside the template. If the slowness is a major concern, perhaps some special support for Python exec-templates could be included, as os-apply-config already has a Python interpreter up.

Not bashing on Mustache btw, it serves its intended purpose (and precisely that) admirably.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-24 13:57:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Works for me

Clint: I would also have leant toward exit codes, but it occurs to me that there are other extensions which are not so easily coded into the remaining value space.

For example, a colleague here was asking how we controlled the file permissions output by the templating step (I think this was for files that were embedding credentials). I suspect that file ownership might also be something we want to control.

Adding the ability to example other output can help in this regard. It has the downside that it requires "executable templates", but for the cases above, not only would we have to run scripts to achieve these goals anyway, but we'd also open a window (which could currently be completely closed) in which the file creds were incorrect.'}, {'account_id': 6488, 'date': '2014-04-14 08:03:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Jan, thanks for the clarification on where you're headed for this.

Permissions on the target files are handled by setting them on the target file first (which sometimes may require creating the target file). os-apply-config will always copy permissions of existing files to the new copy before replacing them with rename.

I've actually been pondering simply deprecating executable templates. Thus far we've not seen any use for them that isn't well handled with regular templates and os-refresh-config scripts.

One thought I have had which is similar to what you're specifying here is to have an optional header on templates which would control meta-information like this. Something like this:

    #-- os-apply-config --
    #create_empty: false
    #mode: 0740
    #--end--

I prefer this because it makes a clear separation between content and control, and it would be quite extensible. I would quite like it if your patch worked more like that as it would work on both executable and regular templates."}, {'account_id': 7579, 'date': '2014-04-14 08:51:40.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

I think I could get behind that idea :-)'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-17 12:19:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

commit_message:
Support control files

Allow templates to provide a control file (EG foo => foo.oac). The
control file must be a single YAML mapping. Directory control files are
not supported yet.

Provide a single valid key, allow_empty, by way of example. If
allow_empty is false, either the target file will not be created or if
there's already a file in place, it will be deleted.

Add requirement on 'six' library for Python 3.3 compatibility.

Advances blueprint oac-header
See spec I8fe7126d7261c1f106d7413bd31aa379e9ae5c3e

Change-Id: Ic6952688e4f8273885192bcd5eda8cb657f5a940

commit_message:
Update nova.conf permission

contains password properties like:
qpid_password=W0lCTTp2MV1kY3ZxcHl2cmFn
neutron_admin_password=W0lCTTp2MV1iY3JhZmducHgtYXJnamJleA==
To avoid unauthorized user to access it and decode the password, this file will be set as 640

Fix bug 1369411

Change-Id: I67606df38ab7829e29eaec686130fa88514be7d1

commit_message:
neutronclient shows low-level logs in console screen

Neutron command lines always display some useless information. This
should be avoided. This commit modifies the default level of console
stream to WARNING.

Closes-bug: #1356735

Change-Id: I997dad9ce3fc3eb795e4e44b27d211fa619c1907

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:44:28.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Add oslo.utils and oslo.serialization

Install the oslo.utils and oslo.serialization libraries from source so
the gate tests run against master.

(This is needed for stable/icehouse to facilitate testing against new
keystoneclient installed via 'git clone' that will depend on oslo.utils.)

Change-Id: I2cb35c9dfd18588e4caa11134e6a34d83324e136
(cherry picked from commit 5cd17f71ca8cf335beeaad55a1b530825bd181c8)

commit_message:
Avoid auto-scheduling for distributed routers

The reason for this is twofold:

- It may relieve contention on DB access while
  both servers and l3 agents are busy setting up
  and syncing routers down respectively.

- It prevents accidental placement of namespaces
  during the L3 sync_routers process, as auto
  scheduling without taking into account the state
  of the L3 agents, as well as the state of the
  routers being processed, may overrule the placement
  decision made during router operations.

Partial-bug: #1356121
Partial-bug: #1359326

Change-Id: Ia677ce212145d6cee65adeb1d8ae594e6ac5e34d

commit_message:
Add $TOP_DIR to the path when calling worlddump script

The missing reference to $TOP_DIR cause stack.sh to fail when called
from outside devstack's directory

Change-Id: I7faec7720896e7dcfe60fa87fb417f22c8801eef

commit_message:
Replace utils.dumps with jsonutils.dumps

In one of the previous patchsets which addresses Bug#1365263
(Idc5ee0fec56b0a0f337433a830647d4f421a8283) utils.dumps was replaced with
jsonutils.dumps. This patch addresses the changes in the remaining files.

Change-Id: Ie8c28d8cd2006e520d1a10ac26111886f63e12da
Closes-bug: 1368835

commit_message:
Don't clear _mounted_shares list in remoteFS while updating

This fix makes the updating of the _mounted_shares list in
remoteFS more of an atomic operation.  Previously this list
would be cleared, then rebuilt.  That allowed a race
condition where operations that took place during this
update would have a list of 0 shares to work with.

Change-Id: I740d8f1b87db911242326a38ff398b81c5974cea
Closes-Bug: #1366083

subject: ldap/core deleteTree not always supported

Not every LDAP server supports CONTROL_TREEDELETE
(OID 1.2.840.113556.1.4.805) e.g. openldap, 389
The LDAP server will respond with ldap.NOT_ALLOWED_ON_NONLEAF
in that case, and the client will have to fallback on a
recursive delete (note this is what openldap
ldapdelete -r does).
Closes-Bug: #1282355

in that case, and the client will have to fallback on a
recursive delete (note this is what openldap
ldapdelete -r does).
Closes-Bug: #1282355

commit_message:
ldap/core deleteTree not always supported

Most LDAP servers do not support CONTROL_TREEDELETE
(OID 1.2.840.113556.1.4.805) e.g. openldap, 389, and many others.
The LDAP server will respond with ldap.NOT_ALLOWED_ON_NONLEAF
in that case, and the client will have to fallback on doing an
LDAP search to get the list of entries to delete, then deleting
the entries in order of child to parent, since LDAP forbids the
deletion of a parent entry which has children.  The simplest way
to generate a child to parent ordering is to delete the entries
in the order of the length of the DN, from longest to shortest.

Closes-Bug: #1282355

Change-Id: I3f08cc4bc890eec9f91945941c3636cb0b30658a

commit_message:
Create an Auth Plugin to pass to users

We pass the service catalog and token data through to consumers via
headers, with the auth plugin work we can create clients that are
authenticated with the incoming token and service catalog.

DocImpact: A new environment option is passed out of auth_token
middleware called `token_auth` which is an authentication plugin that
can be used with a session in a service.

Implements: blueprint create-auth-plugin
Change-Id: I549a421fc73f00126f6ac5f4b5911de2e32de825

commit_message:
Change LOG.exception to LOG.info for skipped tests

The safe setup decorator was presenting skipException in the logs as an error
and so producing lot of noise in tempest.log.

Change-Id: Ia95d6b9dee4eaf4fc8de4bb128f958ef7f693844
Related-bug: #1344581

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-11 00:06:51.000000000', 'message': 'Default to /24 prefix for floating IP range with neutron

When running Tempest parallel tests with neutron, several long-running
tests might create routers and floating IPs, which will result in
IP allocations over the public network.

Increasing the public network size should ensure tests do not fail
due to IP address shortage; this patch also updates the public network
gateway IP address.

Related-Bug: 1253966
Closes-Bug: 1367972

Change-Id: Ie075b3c4d14a07b06c42fd29b09770dd1972aa45

commit_message:
Default to /24 prefix for floating IP range with neutron

When running Tempest parallel tests with neutron, several long-running
tests might create routers and floating IPs, which will result in
IP allocations over the public network.

Increasing the public network size should ensure tests do not fail
due to IP address shortage; this patch also updates the public network
gateway IP address.

Related-Bug: 1253966
Closes-Bug: 1367972

Change-Id: Ie075b3c4d14a07b06c42fd29b09770dd1972aa45
(cherry picked from commit 90234ac4b03426d844b72d251d4cae13fa09cde5)

commit_message:
Add ability to set floating IP Pool names

  - Defaults to 'nova'
  - Allows user to create multiple pools outside
    of the 'nova::manage::floating' definition.

Change-Id: Ia0482cf24a7d9b9589e9b401879268f40e397be3

commit_message:
Set is_public to False by default for volume backed snapshots

This update results in the same behavior that is already implemented
in _create_image where the meta_data for is_public is set to False.

Change-Id: Ie0720d5c847871527db7d9477ca6cb05abe7a1a5
Closes-Bug: #1255316
(cherry picked from commit 0530e02004578a36039111beddf472fcf3e48df6)

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

Question inline... I'm not saying this implementation is wrong, but I'd like to understand the problem domain better."}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-08-23 01:32:56.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

I have concerns about the REST API design for update-cancel. 

As currently implemented, a cancel request is a stack-update request which includes a cancel param.

If a cancel request was made to a heat which doesn't support it then the result might not be a clean error.

Instead I'd like to suggest that stack-cancel be implemented as one of the supported /actions, so stack-cancel is added to the existing actions suspend, resume, and check"}, {'account_id': 4571, 'date': '2014-08-23 01:34:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

As an action, there should also be a new RPC call stack_update_cancel.'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-08-25 07:37:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

(2 comments)

Zane, Steven, thanks for the review. I will rewrite this to use a separate API action and separate RPC call.
Zane, some reply/question inline.'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-08-26 14:50:40.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 8.'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-08-26 16:00:03.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 9.'}, {'account_id': 4257, 'date': '2014-08-26 16:56:50.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7:

Thanks for supporting disable_rollback. Potentially we can cancel an update that takes too long or is behaving strangely, examine the state, and resume the stack-update by reusing the same template, parameters, environment.  
If the user gets impatient and cancel multiple times, are the events just queued up and the subsequent cancels ignored?'}, {'account_id': 9542, 'date': '2014-09-14 17:23:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 13:

Ton, about subsequent events - no, they are not queued up. 

First if we are talking about 'cancel' requests incoming form RPC - those will be ignored simply because we support only cancelling if the stack is in UPDATE_IN_PROGRESS, but after first cancel request it will quite quickly turn to ROLLBACK IN_PROGRESS. 

Second, if we are talking about the events and the 'send' method of the ThreadManager - those are greenlet events [1], and by design they can be used only once. If another message is sent to an already used event an AssertionError will be raised. The docs mention reset() method though, that must allow reusing an event. Since I did not needed it, I did not bothered to use it, but IMO it can be simply added to the code if necessity arises.
So as it is implemented now, the ThreadManager will send the message
to _all_ events registered for given stack, exhausting them as a side effect. It is not a big deal currently, as the only events now are created during start of an initial update procedure, and given stack can not have two updaters running on it (not until convergence that is..), and then events should be cleared up when the thread is done. But of course, there is a field for significant improvement if one wants to reuse events or send messages to specific events only. 

[1] http://eventlet.net/doc/modules/event.html"}, {'account_id': 4715, 'date': '2014-09-15 00:28:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-15 00:28:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13: -Verified

commit_message:
Add RPC API for cancel update stack

Implements cancelling of stack update in progress, for any stack
regardless of disable_rollback status.

As a side-effect, a framework for sending arbitrary one-time signals from
outside into a task running as greenthread is added. ThreadgroupManager
holds references of greenlet events associated with a given stack now.

Implements blueprint cancel-update-stack (partial)

Change-Id: Ic929d42946cf28eeb2a7caea8bf908f492693c09

ofagent: Clean up logging

- Use _LI, _LW, _LE
- Remove localization from debug logs
- Replace LOG.debug calls with @log.log decorator where appropriate

commit_message:
convert the conf value into correct type

If options are set in paste file e.g. api-paste.ini for nova, all
the option values passed into AuthProtocol.conf are string type.
So, we should convert the conf value into correct type.

Change-Id: I0367cd6b54ee49f5db6541840539e7700f241f87
Closes-Bug: #1353315

commit_message:
Ensure a consistent transactional context is used

This change repairs a migration that was using multiple
transactional contexts for a single operation.  Using
a Session implies that operations do not proceed under
"autocommit", so here the autoload operations as well as
migration operations are invoked under a single
connection.  The issue has been exposed due to improvements
in oslo.db which expose SQLite as supporting transactional
DDL.

Change-Id: Ic6673234122e1cf1bc4c05907299bb1938e54a9f
Related-Bug: #1367354

commit_message:
Add delete notification to endpoint grouping

Add delete notification to endpoint grouping so that if a project
or endpoint group is deleted this will automatically force the
deletion of the related project endpoint group association.

Closes-Bug: 1365169
Change-Id: Ic67eaf52ec220bc4ace32a7625af643b3f0818d6

commit_message:
Refactor LDAP backend using context manager for connection

I added context manager support for getting connection in LDAP backend
to replace a large amount try-finally blocks to a simple "with"
statement. So both statements are supported now.

Change-Id: I3e3e29a97e6212177cf755719f404cc24204ea54

[{'created': '2014-09-13 07:50:24.000000000', 'message': "Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910
"}]
commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Correct definition of ironic_host_state.consume_from_instance

Commit d273e33b7739ed18d19d9bcdd00e084c5795e8d6 introduced a change to
the definition of host_state.consume_from_instance in
nova/scheduler/host_manager.py -- but did not update
ironic_host_manager.py and thus broke it.

This patch corrects that by introducing the same change to Ironic's host
manager class.

Change-Id: I4c6425464eb8f89ba76e65b407d2d10f5fd12040
Closes-bug: 1369317

commit_message:
Switch to a custom NotImplemented error

Some code in the drivers might actually raise the standard
NotImplemented error, and that would be a bug to skip a test if that was
the case. In that case we want the test to fail.

So let's switch to a custom exception that is used to skip the test if
it's raised.

Change-Id: Ideafee0b1f008ff32724fb98d6a477bd3976104d

commit_message:
Add IPMI pollster

New pollster to get IPMI sensor data and Intel Node Manager data. IPMI sensor
data includes main types, like Current, Temperature, Voltage and Fan. Node
manager data includes system power and thermal information.

Implements bp ipmi-support
DocImpact: Add new ipmi agent and pollsters

Change-Id: I4e21711cfdb050488dd2ddda1ca80504e63eafaa
Signed-off-by: Zhai Edwin <edwin.zhai@intel.com>

per-sensor data is currently used in ironic, which return a long list including each sensor data.

per-system data is retrieved via a specific IPMI command, which return average/max/min/current value for some time. This data is more readable and useful for high level management.

Method to retrieve them are similar, so putting them together is reasonable.

* add doc for new meter
* produce detailed resource id
* enhance compatibility on platform without node manager'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-09-03 12:26:14.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10: Code-Review-1

Hi 

> Method to retrieve them are similar, so putting them together is reasonable.

The problem with using the same meter name is what happens when a user queries the API to aggregate over, for example, all the hardware.ipmi.power samples for a particular host in a particular timeframe. It makes no sense to average or sum over both per-sensor and system-wide values, as these data mean different things. So I think we will have to ensure that the distinction is made in meter name.

We have an analogous scenario with disk I/O metering. The per-device and instance-wide values are separated into for example disk.write.bytes versus disk.device.write.bytes to prevent this kind of cross-aggregation.

> I'd like to push both of them.

In which case we will need a feature-freeze exception to get this in for juno, as there is no way that second patch will be approved and landed in time for juno-3.

I can request this FFE, but there's no guarantee it will be granted.

Cheers,
Eoghan"}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-03 12:44:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

>The problem with using the same meter name is what happens >when a user queries the API to aggregate over,

Thanks,

(1 comment)

I did some experimenting with ipmitool and sending raw commands to a Dell or HP host (the owner of the host wasn't sure which it was) that does not support node manager. I did that to confirm that the raw commands are specific to Node Manager, and indeed they are.

That leaves us in a bit of confused situation: With the code as is if someone chooses to deploy it on a host that does not support Node Manager they will get some kind of data (the so called "dummy data" in the code comments). This seems like a bad idea. It may be in the long run that this code will support other ipmi commands than the two currently implemented but at no time and under no circumstances should it be capable of delivering fake data in a deployed situation. If node manager isn't supported read_power_all and read_temperature_all should not be called and the pollster should not try to poll things it can't get.

One way of doing this would be to build something into the code that doesn't add the pollsters if the proper support is not there. Another option would be to make sure that the default setup.cfg does not include those pollsters by default.

There's two things that we want to avoid here:

* providing false data
* needlessly running pollsters that won't work

There are probably several ways to achieve this.'}, {'account_id': 2284, 'date': '2014-09-03 16:38:00.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Hi Edwin,

> Is this patch ready after use host-"System current power" as resource_id?

In any case, the release manager has already declared that all patches that were not already in-flight (i.e. fully approved and waiting in the Jenkins verification queue) by circa noon today UTC would have to be deferred (either via a FFE, or to kilo). So we can safely say that the juno-3 boat has been missed, and we're looking at possibly requesting a FFE if we can confidently stand over this patch.

With that in mind, I'd be very interested in hearing your response to cdent's observations above about the dummy data reported in the non-Intel/nodemanager case. Can you explain the intent behind the relevant comment in a bit more detail?

Thanks,
Eoghan'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-04 02:37:59.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 10:

Hi Chris,
>If node manager isn't supported read_power_all and >read_temperature_all should not be called and the pollster >should not try to poll things it can't get.
>One way of doing this would be to build something into the >code that doesn't add the pollsters if the proper support >is not there. Another option would be to make sure that the >default setup.cfg does not include those pollsters by >default.

The 1st option is dynamic pollster that doesn't support now. The 2nd option probably makes hard for deployment. Admin need change setup.cfg and rebuild.
The 3nd option is make pollster tolerant on non-IPMI/NM platform, say return empty list in get_samples.

What's your opinion? BTW, pure IPMI also have the same problem, so does other hardware specific pollster.

>There's two things that we want to avoid here:
>providing false data
>needlessly running pollsters that won't work
>There are probably several ways to achieve this."}, {'account_id': 4992, 'date': '2014-09-04 09:02:55.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 10:

Edwin, might it be possible to de/activate a pollster via an environment variable setting. ENABLE_TEMPERATURE_POLLSTER=True/False.... making it dynamic. Note quite by way of determining whether NodeManager available on a physical compute node.. and avoid the rebuild with a modified setup.cfg that Edwin brought up.

Eoghan/Chris .. with respect to name, I think Edwin chose *.nm.* to highlight that the information came from node manager. Assuming sensor data is of equal quality regardless of source (node manager, ironic approach or otherwise), the name of data element could be source agnostic. But to highlight that it captures min, max, avg etc how about *.agg* or *.aggregate.* 

This raises another question, should we poll and collect but aggregate and singleton values? Which is less compute and storage intensive -- aggregate by sensor agent or aggregating by way of ceilometer agent? Is it more likely that we would modify the time window over which statistics are aggregated.

Would we want to provide a config parameter to determine what is polled for -- singleton versus aggregate -- this could be a future feature enhancement little patch.

Regards,
Malini'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-04 11:46:26.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 11.'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-04 11:49:47.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 11:

* For IPMI sensor data, use host-name + sensor ID as resource_id
  for NM data, use host-name + "System current temperature" as resource_id

  Use different level of capability: none, IPMI, Node Manager. 
  None: always get empty data
  IPMI: can get IPMI sensor data like Ironic, but empty data for NM
  Node Manager: Both IPMI sensor data and NM data

We have so many 'nodes' and 'managers' in OpenStack and Ceilometer already. Since the Node Manager here is Intel specific, wouldn't it make sense to call it Intel Node Manager everywhere? There might be a different ARM Node Manager one day :-)

Additional comment inline about the parameter description."}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-12 08:33:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 20:

Nejc?
Yes, node and manager is common, but "Node Manager" is the term to describe Intel's management tech based on IPMI. And currently no conflict.

I can add some comments in b/ceilometer/ipmi/platform/node_manager.py to explain it. But change everywhere including code is not feasible.

I'll modify the init_retries description according to your comments.

Thanks,
Edwin'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:13:36.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 21.'}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:15:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

Nejc

Thanks,
Edwin'}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:28:50.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

It's Intel's management technology and that's precisely why I'd prefer to see it include the word Intel. It's not generic at all, but currently, it could be assumed as such. It's not about conflicts, it's about concepts and code clarity.

Why is it not feasible to change it in the code?"}, {'account_id': 11235, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:41:04.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

Nejc,

There are many class, function and variable names. It's not necessary to append intel to each of them. Take kernel source for example, no need to add intel/amd/ibm to each of term in source code as we organize them well via arch/XXX.

I have ceilometer/ipmi/platform here for this. If you like, I can change the name to intel_node_manager.py, which indicate everything inside this file is vender specific."}, {'account_id': 8052, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:43:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 21:

Yep, I agree that filename and class name would suffice. Sorry, I didn't mean for you to change every function :-). Thanks for being so responsive!

commit_message:
Add IPMI support

Adds IPMI engine to get sensor data or system power/thermal information on
IPMI capable node, improves overall efficiency and maximizes overall usage for
data center.

Implements bp ipmi-support

Change-Id: I77c881fdaf39c69cfa990468110dbbfa1f8df8dd
Signed-off-by: Zhai Edwin <edwin.zhai@intel.com>

commit_message:
v2: handle InvalidBDM exceptions from compute API

The compute API _validate_bdm method can raise an
InvalidBDMVolume exception which the nova v2 API
servers extension wasn't handling.

This adds InvalidBDM (the base class for various
invalid BDM exception types) handling in the v2
servers create method.

The v3 API is already handling individual
InvalidBDM exceptions. This change also cleans up
a duplicate exception handled in that code.

Unit tests are added for the v2 and v3 API
extensions for InvalidBDMVolume.

Change-Id: I1f4182e612fbe366fa0733df785ec0f6fcc95196
Closes-Bug: #1368939

commit_message:
labs: osbashauto exit on script error

Make osbashout abort if a client-side scripts returns an error; use a
file named error in the status directory to signal the problem and to
store the name of the offending script for use by Windows batch scripts.

Have osbash.sh and the Windows batch scripts exit when an error file
appears.

Change-Id: I6722e75c9c23b99e5ed25b00429026c2e0ff6a12

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This can cause docs jobs to fail if the project errors out on
warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
Adds a test for raw_cpu_arch in _node_resource

Commit 5fd0500e7e262c602dc7bbbff456326598da41bc
makes it such that the cpu_arch is not
made canonical for scheduling, this adds a unit
test to cover the change.

Change-Id: I89080a0178b1098c2a297b7268fad279ece680c2
Related-Bug: #1366859

commit_message:
Remove snapshot_id from _volume_snapshot_create()

There is an argument "snapshot_id" in _volume_snapshot_create(), but
the argument is not used in _volume_snapshot_create().
This patch removes it for cleanup.

Change-Id: Ibaad290e149a863c749c74ace3ba702870b8dd1b

commit_message:
Fix parsing sloppiness from iscsiadm discover

As reported by a user, iscsiadm might spew some other random gorp when
it starts up, and if it does, nova explodes poorly. Put a modicum of
sanity testing into the parsing of the output to make this less
likely.

Change-Id: Iaf55438bb3ec412187158e80f9fbc1d8e7071207
Closes-Bug: #1308649

[{'created': '2014-08-26 10:41:17.000000000', 'message': 'Add reset-state function for backups

Since there are volume reset-state function and snapshot reset-state
function,
backup also needs reset-state as well.
When creating or restoring backup, it may leave the backup stucked in
creating
or restoring status due to database down or rabbitmq down, etc.
Currently we could only solve these problems by restarting cinder-backup
service.
This BP is to provide another mean for administrators to solve these
problems by
calling backup reset state API, instead of directly restarting
cinder-backup service.

blueprint Add reset-state function for backups

commit_message:
Add reset-state function for backups

Since there are volume reset-state function and snapshot reset-state
function, backup also needs reset-state as well.
When creating or restoring backup, it may leave the backup stuck in
creating or restoring status due to database down or rabbitmq down, etc.
Currently we could only solve these problems by restarting cinder-backup
service.

This BP is to provide another means for administrators to solve these
problems by calling backup reset state API, instead of directly
restarting cinder-backup service.

DocImpact: Support reset backup status

blueprint support-reset-state-for-backup

Change-Id: Icd677a0b48083894bcd969d5199fa91b307080de

Roger, if there's no ping reply, should we continue (like here in this script) or maybe abort (because cluster will not be properly configured?)"}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-09-10 13:33:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

The simple tests I put into some of the scripts write something to the log files to help with diagnosis. This bug (assuming the fix is correct) was bad because it left no trace in the log file.

Right now, we don't have a method for aborting. We can stop a script, but then the next script will be executed, and you will never know unless you check the log files (or realize the cluster is broken). That is one of the things I am currently working on. I hope to have a usable method for dealing with errors in all VM scripts soonish (the previous two fixes for scripts were due to that work).

So yeah, I agree with you, and I hope to address your concern with a changeset landing in the not-too-distant future."}, {'account_id': 11889, 'date': '2014-09-10 13:43:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1

There is no hurry to merge as long as there are no follow-up patches that depend on it.'}, {'account_id': 11109, 'date': '2014-09-13 12:30:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
labs: move network-api IP address

Eth3 is used for a bridge and should therefore not have an IP address.
With the network-api address remaining on eth3, we can't talk to
controller-api.

This patch moves the IP address to the switch-internal network device
of the bridge, br-ex.

Change-Id: I2a52844a160fe7ccd95e8d1aa16eb2d451dd605f

Eric, Here are my findings.

1) requests.post is correct since we already send and receive data using SOAP HTTP Binding as mentioned in the wsdl
2) Currently we don't allow anyone to specify userid/password for a basic auth OR ntlm via suds's existing urllib2 interface so we don't need that support
3) Note that Login/Logout is using webservices calls and NOT basic auth or ntlm
4) Currently we don't allow anyone to specify a client certificate either so that's out of question as well
5) Yes, the code supports both HTTP and HTTPS.

commit_message:
VMware: Enable vCenter SSL certificate validation

During https/ssl communication the server certificate of
a vCenter is not validated during https handshake process.
This patch will enable the certificate validation against root
certificate of the vCenter to validate the identity of that vCenter.
Nova, Cinder etc will need to specify the cacert parameter
for this to take effect.

Ported from Id: Ic24951630698068321bb62d3098de8344a35c5d0

Closes-Bug: #1276207
Co-Authored-By: Johnson koil raj <johnson.raj@hp.com>
Change-Id: I422e6d4df4e392334c0ce47e6f5b017a8c95f61a
