commit_message:
Fix AttributeError in VolumeSnapshot

This fixes a regression introduced in
Hiding "Launch as Instance" if volume is not bootable.

Change-Id: I9c45a1f5f4e3a096843ba6547dbf76387501f447
Closes-Bug: 1368732

[{'created': '2014-08-20 14:23:56.000000000', 'message': 'VMware: Remove redundant extend disk API call

Extend virtual disk API is called during volume creation from image if
the image size is less than volume size. In the case of streamOptimized
and sparse vmdk images, the size of the virtual disk created from the
image can be greater than image size and equal to the volume size. For
example, streamOptimized image created from a new 1GB volume has size
69120 bytes and the size of the virtual disk created from this image
is 1GB. Therefore, relying on image size to invoke extend API might
result in VIM API fault, if the virtual disk size is same as the target
size (volume size). The fix is to read the current virtual disk size to
decide whether extend disk needs to be invoked or not.

Closes-Bug: #1301854
Change-Id: I990ac0b9aef68b3ef8b6d67188db8d44b5c29599

commit_message:
VMware: Remove redundant extend disk API call

Extend virtual disk API is called during volume creation from image if
the image size is less than volume size. In the case of streamOptimized
and sparse vmdk images, the size of the virtual disk created from the
image can be greater than image size and equal to the volume size. For
example, streamOptimized image created from a new 1GB volume has size
69120 bytes and the size of the virtual disk created from this image
is 1GB. Therefore, relying on image size to invoke extend API might
result in VIM API fault, if the virtual disk size is same as the target
size (volume size). The fix is to read the current virtual disk size to
decide whether extend disk needs to be invoked or not.

Closes-Bug: #1301854
Change-Id: I990ac0b9aef68b3ef8b6d67188db8d44b5c29599

commit_message:
Destroy Datera export target after detach

Since there is only one lun associated with each target export object in
the Datera backend, we will destroy the target export object after
detaching the volume so they don't build up. This patch also fixes some
missing values for formatted strings.

Closes-Bug: #1368381
Change-Id: Id44ac4bb385ab39af50865a295938861ca977fa3

[{'created': '2014-08-19 19:20:54.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Consider numa_topology when booting

This patch hooks all the already introduced pieces together to enable
NUMA aware placement of instances.

The libvirt driver boot process now looks into the NUMA topology field
of both instance and the host it is being booted on, and based on that
adds some more configuration to the generated guest XML.

In case the host is NUMA capable, but the instance has not requested
a NUMA topology, we will try to pack the instance into a single cell.
If that fails, currently we will not make further attempts (although
an improvement could be to expose the underlying topology to the
instance).

In case the host is NUMA capable, and instance has requested a specific
NUMA topology, we will try to pin the vCPUs of different instance NUMA
cells to the corresponding host NUMA cells, and also expose the instance
NUMA topology to the guest OS.

'}, {'created': '2014-08-22 18:49:22.000000000', 'message': 'libvirt: Consider numa_topology when booting

This patch hooks all the already introduced pieces together to enable
NUMA aware placement of instances.

The libvirt driver boot process now looks into the NUMA topology field
of both instance and the host it is being booted on, and based on that
adds some more configuration to the generated guest XML.

In case the host is NUMA capable, but the instance has not requested
a NUMA topology, we will try to pack the instance into a single cell.
If that fails, currently we will not make further attempts (although
an improvement could be to expose the underlying topology to the
instance).

In case the host is NUMA capable, and instance has requested a specific
NUMA topology, we will try to pin the vCPUs of different instance NUMA
cells to the corresponding host NUMA cells, and also expose the instance
NUMA topology to the guest OS.

We will still try to respect CONF.vcpu_pin_set option and avoid pinning
to CPUs that are not in this set.

Change-Id: I611d44ab75475028f63c2b7f8a0d2ef37d85be6e
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
libvirt: Consider numa_topology when booting

This patch hooks all the already introduced pieces together to enable
NUMA aware placement of instances.

The libvirt driver boot process now looks into the NUMA topology field
of both instance and the host it is being booted on, and based on that
adds some more configuration to the generated guest XML.

In case the host is NUMA capable, but the instance has not requested
a NUMA topology, we will try to pack the instance into a single cell.
If that fails, currently we will not make further attempts (although
an improvement could be to expose the underlying topology to the
instance).

In case the host is NUMA capable, and instance has requested a specific
NUMA topology, we will try to pin the vCPUs of different instance NUMA
cells to the corresponding host NUMA cells, and also expose the instance
NUMA topology to the guest OS.

We will still try to respect CONF.vcpu_pin_set option and avoid pinning
to CPUs that are not in this set.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I611d44ab75475028f63c2b7f8a0d2ef37d85be6e
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-18 16:04:09.000000000', 'message': 'Add the NUMATopologyFilter

This patch adds the basic NUMA filter that will take the proposed
instance topology and try to match it against that of a host.

The matching will be done in the following manner:

 * Filter will try to match the exact cells of the instance to those of
   the host. It *will not* attempt to pack the instance onto the host.
 * It will consider the standard over-subscription limits for each cell,
   and provide limits to the compute host accordingly.
 * In case instance has no topology defined, it will be considered for
   any host.
 * In case the host is not a NUMA host - it will be considered by this
   filter always

DocImpact

Change-Id: I8788dde69524c8a32a41ce31a96c89f9b09e91ce
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Add the NUMATopologyFilter

This patch adds the basic NUMA filter that will take the proposed
instance topology and try to match it against that of a host.

The matching will be done in the following manner:

 * Filter will try to match the exact NUMA cells of the instance to those
   of the host. It *will not* attempt to pack the instance onto the host.
 * It will consider the standard over-subscription limits for each cell,
   and provide limits to the compute host accordingly.
 * If instance has no topology defined, it will be considered for any host.
 * If instance has a topology defined, it will be considered only for NUMA
   capable hosts.

DocImpact

Change-Id: I8788dde69524c8a32a41ce31a96c89f9b09e91ce
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

"}, {'created': '2014-08-24 10:43:19.000000000', 'message': "Make HostManager track NUMA usage

This patch adds tracking of NUMA usage in scheduler's HostManager class,
by adding it to the HostState, and making sure it gets updated along
with all the other usage data.

We also make sure that we can extract NUMA usage from an instance that
is set as part of the request_specs dictionary (which sadly uses
objects_base.obj_to_primitive for stuff that get sent over the wire
which means they lose all the versioning information).

Change-Id: Id31c9a7fd54b918b3d38abb61b305cf7048a6a7d
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Make HostManager track NUMA usage

This patch adds tracking of NUMA usage in scheduler's HostManager class,
by adding it to the HostState, and making sure it gets updated along
with all the other usage data.

Change-Id: Id31c9a7fd54b918b3d38abb61b305cf7048a6a7d
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Sync with latest oslo-incubator

Last commit: 32e7f0b56f527427544050f251999f3de588ac93

This patch syncs the python-keystoneclient with olso-incubator as I
need this patch 4ef01931 which fixes a bug that's I am hitting in
another client which uses the keystoneclient.

Closes-bug: 1277565

Change-Id: I22f10f4fe27be16a6808b75c154ee342fea2bdda

commit_message:
Add to configure bind_ip on the storage nodes

The bind_ip under [DEFAULT] section of account-server.conf,
container-server.conf,object-server.conf files under /etc/swift of the
storage nodes need to be changed to the STORAGE_LOCAL_NET_IP.

Change-Id: Icfb92294466d5f38ae5abc80e2e6165802aec58f
Closes-Bug: #1364268

Mark, that was the approach we initially had.
But then we found out that did not work because of developers adding tests that did not clear all resources they created, and differences in db schemas across plugin.

For the latter we'd need both DB migration healing and removal of schema autogeneration; for the former somebody already attempted at writing automated cleanup code, but that experiment did not work.

I also seem to recall it was evaluated the cost of generating an in-memory sqlite schema was actually contained, but the schema has grown a lot since then, so we'd need to evaluate that again."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-09 08:14:33.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: -Verified

commit_message:
UTs: Disable auto deletion of ports/subnets/nets

Change the behavior of the unit test context managers
for ports, networks, and subnets to skip the deletion
of the objects they create.

Adds explicit delete calls to the tests that require
deletion of the objects.

This is the first patch in a series to eliminate the
automatic deletion of objects created during tests to
improve test performance and make testing more explicit.

Implements: blueprint remove-unit-test-autodeletion
Change-Id: Ifc4490b121310ad64e18936e6fd94a2c9a1e36f2

I have concerns about this approach. /etc/fstab and /etc/mtab are not exactly the same. /etc/fstab contains information on various file systems on the host, while /etc/mtab only contains information on mounted devices. Overwriting /etc/fstab with /etc/mtab completely doesn't seem safe to me. Can we add/remove  individual mount entry one at a time to/from /etc/fstab instead of overwriting the whole file?"}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-12 03:54:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-12 05:49:36.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Xing,

The real difference between /etc/fstab and /etc/mtab is in following:

mtab shows "currently" mounted filesystems, modified by "mount". fstab shows filesystems that will be mounted on boot of host, on "mount -a" operation or used as defaults to mount something via "mount" operation.'}, {'account_id': 7534, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:48:48.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2: Code-Review-1

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-12 09:56:17.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 7534, 'date': '2014-09-12 10:11:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

(1 comment)'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-13 05:29:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Hi Valeriy,

What you said is correct, however, overwriting /etc/fstab completely with /etc/mtab doesn't seem safe to me.

/etc/fstab contains information that is not in /etc/mtab. By copying /etc/mtab over to /etc/fstab, you'll loose information that is only in /etc/fstab.

See the following lines from http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Fstab: 

"The fstab file typically lists all available disks and disk partitions, and indicates how they are to be initialized or otherwise integrated into the overall system's file system."

It's better to add a mount entry to /etc/fstab one at a time, rather than overwrite it completely.'}, {'account_id': 8851, 'date': '2014-09-13 06:10:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Make block devices mounts permanent within service instances

Restart of service VM does not save mount state of block device for share.
So, if we do not restart m-shr we have export to dir that links not to
block device, but to root filesystem of service VM.

Changes:
- added sync method of temp and permanent fs mount files;
- changed lock value for mount operations from share id to service instance id,
  because any action changes common config file;
- updated related unittests;

Change-Id: I874d84f5342208906379aba5572540a984f79f03
Closes-Bug: #1367731

commit_message:
API boot process sets NUMA topology for instances

This patch makes the API instance boot path look at the bits that can
contain requested topology, generate the desired topology and make sure
it is saved on the instance itself.

We also need to account for the flavor passed to
VirtNUMAInstanceTopology.get_constraints not being an actual Flavor
object, and work with db layer objects.

Change-Id: Ia3f3446da99a04e2d8152acb7d0bda7a1d502c83
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

commit_message:
Increase share-network default quota

Now Manila has too small quota for share networks, that affects gate tests with
exception "ShareNetworksLimitExceeded".

Changes:
- increased quota from 5 to 10;
- updated description of quota with proper info.

Change-Id: I1e3127780785ec689d02a4a0bcce42d903df7d72
Closes-Bug: #1368460

The API samples of scheduler-hints contains "hypervisor" and "near"
attributes, but the attributes do not exist in the scheduler-hints
parameter of "create a server" API. This patch changes them to the
existing "same_host" attribute.

commit_message:
Fix scheduler-hints example

The API samples of scheduler-hints contains "hypervisor" and "near"
attributes, but the attributes do not exist in the scheduler-hints
parameter of "create a server" API. This patch changes them to the
existing "same_host" attribute.

Change-Id: Ia6b34fe5b0327b4499df0e0dac623eb42fb07285
Closes-Bug: #1285456

commit_message:
Hunormous file rename for v3 to v2.1 for Compute

Nova team decided to do a minor version to 2.1
rather than move to v3 so the API docs need to
reflect that. Still marked Experimental.

Closes-bug:1367307

commit_message:
Make resource tracker track NUMA usage

This patch makes the resource tracker actually track and update NUMA
usage from instance andd resize claims, and periodic resource updates.

Change-Id: Iea9d076cb37e530f442faefacd2a59b6b6225e92
Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-05 14:04:40.000000000', 'message': 'Hook NUMA topology checking into claims

This patch adds the ability to test claims against NUMA topology exposed
by the host and instance. This is currently a no-op as no code in the
scheduler will actually attempt to set the limits against numa_topology.

This patch also changes the resource_tracker resize_claim method to
accept the image_metada of the instance as it is used (alongside flavor) to
calculate the new topology that will be exposed after the resize is
done.

The resource tracker will not do any actual usage tracking yet - this
will be done in a follow-up patch.

Change-Id: I07b690243d481c855c5e706f968cf224b336a1a0

This patch adds the ability to test claims against NUMA topology exposed
by the host and instance. This is currently a no-op as no code in the
scheduler will actually attempt to set the limits against numa_topology.
Since getting the NUMA topology of the instance may require an additional
db roundtrip, we try to avoid getting it unless absolutely necessary.

This patch also changes the resource_tracker resize_claim method to
accept the image_metada of the instance as it is used (alongside flavor)
to calculate the new topology that will be exposed after the resize is
done.

The resource tracker will not do any actual usage tracking yet - this
will be done in a follow-up patch.

commit_message:
Hook NUMA topology checking into claims

This patch adds the ability to test claims against NUMA topology exposed
by the host and instance. This is currently a no-op as no code in the
scheduler will actually attempt to set the limits against numa_topology.
Since getting the NUMA topology of the instance may require an additional
db roundtrip, we try to avoid getting it unless absolutely necessary.

This patch also changes the resource_tracker resize_claim method to
accept the image_metada of the instance as it is used (alongside flavor)
to calculate the new topology that will be exposed after the resize is
done.

The resource tracker will not do any actual usage tracking yet - this
will be done in a follow-up patch.

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: I07b690243d481c855c5e706f968cf224b336a1a0

I do think this is a good idea, the only problem is that it provides the current definition of a flavor, not the one used to create an instance. Flavors are mutable, so if a change is made to the definition the flavor will not match the instance.

To follow the semantics there is no getting away from copying the extra_specs to the metadata or the instance or in fact both.

The other alternative is to make flavors immutable.

Having said that I still think caching the data is a good idea instead of going to the database all the time.'}, {'account_id': 7461, 'date': '2014-08-28 13:17:44.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 21:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-04 17:48:18.000000000', 'message': "Cache flavors in the resource tracker

Currently we would rely on getting the flavor information from the
instance system_metadata in the resource tracker allowing us to avoid
additional DB calls unless data is not available (for legacy reasons)
which we assume is a rare event. This however makes it impossible to use
flavor extra_specs in the resource tracker without adding them to the
instance system_metadata as well, which is proven to be a Bad Idea for
overall performance.

We deal with that in this patch by doing a single query for all the
Flavor objects our tracked instances relate to, and caching them on the
resource tracker object itself (purging the cache on every periodic
update). This will allow us to query the extra_specs when we will need
them (currently we add a flag for this but it's not used thus far). for
the cost of one additional DB query and a conductor roundtrip.

It is worth noting that flavor data stashed on the instance as system_metadata
can go stale once the flavor is changed in the DB, in which case it is
possible to get old flavor data, paired with new(er) extra_specs. This
does not seem like a big concern at the moment,

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: I83ca863d521c579d8f1fe6168d7b1096af9f14f1

can go stale once the flavor is changed in the DB, in which case it is
possible to get old flavor data, paired with new(er) extra_specs. This
does not seem like a big concern at the moment,

Change-Id: I83ca863d521c579d8f1fe6168d7b1096af9f14f1
"}, {'created': '2014-08-25 12:34:57.000000000', 'message': "Cache flavors in the resource tracker

Currently we would rely on getting the flavor information from the
instance system_metadata in the resource tracker allowing us to avoid
additional DB calls unless data is not available (for legacy reasons)
which we assume is a rare event. This however makes it impossible to use
flavor extra_specs in the resource tracker without adding them to the
instance system_metadata as well, which is proven to be a Bad Idea for
overall performance.

We deal with that in this patch by doing a single query for all the
Flavor objects our tracked instances relate to, and caching them on the
resource tracker object itself (purging the cache on every periodic
update). This will allow us to query the extra_specs when we will need
them (currently we add a flag for this but it's not used thus far). for
the cost of one additional DB query and a conductor roundtrip.

It is worth noting that flavor data stashed on the instance as system_metadata
can go stale once the flavor is changed in the DB, in which case it is
possible to get old flavor data, paired with new(er) extra_specs. This
does not seem like a big concern at the moment,

commit_message:
Stash numa-related flavor extra_spec items in system_metadata

This is a temporary measure to avoid having to add additional persistence
of extra_specs data simply to facilitate merging the NUMA patches. Only
the numa_cpus.* and numa_mem.* items are saved from extra_specs at
this time. The expectation is that this will quickly come out in kilo
when the rest of the flavor information stashed in system_metadata gets
removed and stored elsewhere.

Blueprint: virt-driver-numa-placement
Change-Id: I83ca863d521c579d8f1fe6168d7b1096af9f14f1

This does look like it'll solve the issue of blocking the periodic tasks, but it still seems like the check for a current task state should be moved outside of the sync lock since the instance data is not updated after holding the lock.

For the case where an instance is being deployed, the deploy logic will sync on the instance uuid and there will be at task_state set.  When the periodic task comes by, an individual thread will be spun off to attempt the sync lock.  The thread will spin until the instance is done with deployment.  Once that occurs, the original instance object retrieved before the lock was attempted will be checked for a task_state and it'll be set, so the whole spin off of a thread, and waiting on the sync will be for nothing really.

Am I wrong here?  But regardless of that it solves the bigger issue.  +1  ;-)"}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-05 18:56:59.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

After looking this over some more and talking with Brian in IRC, some notes:

1. there are a lot of test that have this: self.compute = importutils.import_object(CONF.compute_manager),

2. however, only 2 call self.compute._sync_power_states directly and those are the ones changed here that stub out the greenpool.

3. so we're probably safe - at some point if someone writes some new code to test _sync_power_states then they'll need to stub out the greenpool if it's not in those modules - or extend test_compute.BaseTestCase (which a lot of the other compute manager integration style tests do already)

4. My main concern was the ec2 cloud tests since they start up a compute service but (a) they aren't calling the sync method and (b) periodic tasks are disabled in the unit tests, so we should be OK.

[{'created': '2014-08-29 15:27:24.000000000', 'message': 'Process power state syncs asynchronously

The instance locking introduced in
cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 keeps the power state sane
between stop and the periodic task power sync.  However, locking on
an instance in the periodic task thread can potentially lock
that thread for a long time.

Example:
1) User boots an instance.  The instance gets locked by uuid.
2) Driver spawn begins and the image starts downloading from glance.
3) During spawn, periodic tasks run.  Sync power states tries to grab
the same instance lock by uuid.
4) Periodic task thread hangs until the driver spawn completes in
another greenthread.

This scenario results in nova-compute appearing unresponsive for
a long time.

Change-Id: Idbc00ddfcb7a6816433863ed1686ad8f7477d99b
'}, {'created': '2014-08-29 19:46:50.000000000', 'message': 'Process power state syncs asynchronously

cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 keeps the power state sane
between stop and the periodic task power sync.  However, locking on
an instance in the periodic task thread can potentially lock
that thread for a long time.

Fix this condition by executing power syncs in a background GreenPool.
Limit the syncs to 1 at a time per instance.

Closes-Bug: 1363231

commit_message:
Process power state syncs asynchronously

The instance locking introduced in
cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 keeps the power state sane
between stop and the periodic task power sync.  However, locking on
an instance in the periodic task thread can potentially lock
that thread for a long time.

Fix this condition by executing power syncs in a background GreenPool.
Limit the syncs to 1 at a time per instance.

Closes-Bug: 1363231

Change-Id: Idbc00ddfcb7a6816433863ed1686ad8f7477d99b

commit_message:
Changes to support FWaaS in a DVR based environment

Implementation of Spec to address the changes required for FWaaS
to work with DVR to handle:
* Perimeter Firewall support on N - S traffic
* Ensure that E - W DVR traffic is not broken.

DocImpact

Change-Id: Iba78e534ccf347ea6270aabc939a489dd40a7b9e
Implements: blueprint neutron-dvr-fwaas

commit_message:
Nova-net: fix server side deallocate_for_instance()

Client side of the network RPC API sets 'requested_networks'
parameter in deallocate_for_instance() call,
while server side expected 'fixed_ips' parameter.
This patch fixes server side so it handles 'requested_networks'

Closes-Bug: #1350355

Change-Id: If9554a2e98397c5e63e929e1606d99dd2328262c

recheck-migrations'}, {'account_id': 5292, 'date': '2014-03-19 04:08:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve

So I think there is at least one code path where an exception raised before would have bubbled up through to the API. Even though we don't handle it, the user would know something went wrong with the delete. But it doesn't happen in all cases (in compute manager it just logs and throws away the exception). 

I think its kind of bad that the user is never told that part of the deletion failed. But I don't think there's any simple solution to this problem (perhaps delete should be task eventually too). And this does fix a real problem of not even trying to delete ports if one fails. So I'm just +1 for now."}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-03-19 04:27:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

The problem is this would fail when an instance is being deleted so we don't currently have a way for the user to see this. I agree the  nova tasks would be a good usecase for this. Also, if a port failed to delete before this patch the user would still have no way to know that, that occurred via the api. 

The only way the user can 100% avoid these orphaned ports is if they pre-create the ports themselves and pass those in. Then they deal with deleting the ports when they want to."}, {'account_id': 4395, 'date': '2014-03-20 00:22:18.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 6.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-03-20 00:22:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

I think I like the fix, but with the commit message was a bit more explicit about the change.

I *think* what we're now saying is:
- we always try to delete all ports create by Nova, even if some fail
- during recovery from a network failure in instance creation, we don't raise an exception for failures (Because the instance is going to go to an error state anyway) 
- during a deletion we do raise an exception, because we don't the instance to be deleted (and lose the reference to the ports)  

Is that right.  If so can we update the commit message and/or capture this in comments if you have to respin.

I still think it would be good if we could free up all the other resources on the host and set the host to None when the only error is a Neutron one - so that the instance doesn't count against the host anymore from a Nova resource perspective, but maybe that belongs in a subsequent patch.  This is a big enough step forwards to not block on that."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:13:27.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 23.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-09-12 15:19:10.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
neutronv2: attempt to delete all ports

Previously when deleting ports during allocate
or deallocate, the operation would fail on the
first non-404 error encountered. We now loop
through all of the ports and attempt the delete.

In the allocate flow we don't raise any errors
since the instance is set to ERROR anyway and
we're just trying to cleanup.

In the deallocate flow we attempt to delete all
of the ports and if there was a non-404 exception
we raise that at the end so the overall instance
delete operation fails.

Change-Id: Ibf68e0b4770b09ee32f187b85f2ca96984117e0b
Closes-bug: #1292243
Co-Authored-By: Dan Smith <dansmith@redhat.com>
Co-Authored-By: Sean Dague <sean@dague.net>
Co-Authored-By: Matt Riedemann <mriedem@us.ibm.com>

[{'created': '2014-06-09 04:32:29.000000000', 'message': 'Only support client plugins

This change removes client memoization, and utility methods for
clients contributed via a Clients method.

All clients must now be contributed via a client plugin.

This change also removes the cloud_backend configuration option
since different cloud backends can now simply be contributed
by having alternative client plugins available to load in the
configured plugin_dirs.

commit_message:
Only support client plugins

This change removes client memoization, and utility methods for
clients contributed via a Clients method.

All clients must now be contributed via a client plugin.

This change also removes the cloud_backend configuration option
since different cloud backends can now simply be contributed
by having alternative client plugins available to load in the
configured plugin_dirs.

Change-Id: I2c25eb639cc8024bd98b99934ebfd026ffe9f6dd

commit_message:
Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages

When a ProcessExecutionError is thrown by processutils.execute(), the
exception may contain information such as password. Upstream
applications that just log the message (as several appear to do) could
inadvertently expose these passwords to a user with read access to the
log files. It is therefore considered prudent to invoke
strutils.mask_password() on the command, stdout and stderr in the
exception.

Cherry-pick from 853d8f9897f8563851441108a9be26b10908c076
Partial-Bug: #1343604

Conflicts:
	nova/openstack/common/processutils.py

Change-Id: I9741dcdebdb4bed295ddc5ec4c4b117fffcfe88c

commit_message:
Make strutils.mask_password more secure

Make some enhancements to strutils.mask_password to allow it to
catch more cases of passwords in strings.

The following is a listing of patterns that will be handled. The
keyword that mask_password uses (a list of four now) is represented
by <key> and the password is shown as <password>. Quotes (both single
and double) are represented as <quote>.

--<key> <password>
--<key> <quote><password><quote>
<key> = <password>
<key> = <quote><password><quote>

All existing tests and patterns are still handled.

Cherry-pick from 61d5de69850bf082b2aa45747104b2b5be764c21
Partial-Bug: #1345233

Conflicts:
	nova/openstack/common/strutils.py

Change-Id: I693baaf225c5b393401d499d14f271cadb63eb2c

commit_message:
Sync latest processutils from oslo-incubator

This sync is primarily being done to pull in commit
63c99a0f so that passwords are masked in exception and
error messages.

------------------------------------------------

oslo-incubator head:

commit 80a08a413fb0f23a056eca2d273b167f0a09bab6
Merge: 83c4098 d73f3b1
Author: Jenkins <jenkins@review.openstack.org>
Date:   Mon Aug 25 14:32:36 2014 +0000

    Merge "Remove unused/mutable default args"

-----------------------------------------------

The sync pulls in the following changes (newest to oldest):

63c99a0f - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages
e184dd36 - Fix exception message in openstack.common.processutils.execute
d6b55fb2 - Remove `processutils` dependency on `log`

-----------------------------------------------

Cherry-pick from ff0f112bb41fa0f01692f6c4eb8a20d9a4fa8a7c
Partial-bug: 1343604

Conflicts:
	cinder/openstack/common/processutils.py

Change-Id: Ia92aab76fa83d01c5fbf6f9d31df2463fc26ba5c

commit_message:
Sync latest strutils from oslo-incubator

We have had a request from Tristan Cacqueray to pull in the latest
strutils.  The request is driven by a need to get improvements in
place that make strutils.mask_password more secure.

-------------------------------------

Head of oslo-incubator:
commit 80a08a413fb0f23a056eca2d273b167f0a09bab6
Merge: 83c4098 d73f3b1
Author: Jenkins <jenkins@review.openstack.org>
Date:   Mon Aug 25 14:32:36 2014 +0000

    Merge "Remove unused/mutable default args"

--------------------------------------

This sync pulls in the following change:

66142c34 - Make strutils.mask_password more secure

--------------------------------------

Cherry-pick from beca4db62f16f27df1af2e4d8ba12fcbe416ffb1
Partial-bug: 1345233

Conflicts:
	cinder/openstack/common/strutils.py

Change-Id: Ie51d316a30bed40996db6cd860dbb9cb173e5ac6

commit_message:
Ironic: don't canonicalize extra_specs data

Don't canonicalize the cpu_arch extra_specs field. This is important
because the scheduler filters which use extra specs don't canonicalize
things either and as such you'll have mismatched fields causing
instances not to get scheduled.

This was recently changed as part of the Ironic -> Nova driver patch
series. We still want to canonicalize supported_instances though...

Change-Id: I9342213b5433113816142b1f737119065e9f077f
Closes-bug: #1366859

(dunno why my inlined comment lines are not soft-wrapping, so reproducing here)

Yep, this makes more sense. The original fix was restricted to address the case that needed addressing then (when dealing with data whose size cannot be predetermined), but this class can't support random access in any meaningful way. As for why the code was no-op on seek and returning the max transfer size on tell, I can only postulate it might be to support use case of quckly determining the file-like's size with 
   f.seek(0,2)
   size = f.tell()
That's not a good justification for the code though.

Following up comment:
On second thought, right or wrong the motivation behind the original implementation was probably to get non-chunked http transfer to work as expected.
seek()+tell() was probably used to figure out the value to use in the Content-Length: header field. Can you verify if that is still the case or not before we okay this?"}, {'account_id': 8027, 'date': '2014-07-24 08:50:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

seek:

tell:
The BlockingQueue methods are called in FileReadWriteTask and ImageWriter and there are no tell() invocations in FileReadWriteTask.
The Content-Length is set only in FileWriteHandle and VmdkWriteHandle.

What if the image service client is calling tell()?

https://github.com/openstack/python-glanceclient/blob/master/glanceclient/common/utils.py#L281
This is the only reference I could find and there are no issues here.'}, {'account_id': 8027, 'date': '2014-07-25 06:01:40.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 1:

Yeah I was referring to the image service's interaction with the pipe.
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/85031/ seems to be addressing the very same problem that the existing code tried to address as well. I don't think things will break with this change, but this patch as well as what was done in 85031 forces all transfers to glance to be chunked based. This may or may not be what we want; just want to call out the change in behavior. 
Adding Arnaud who may have some experience comparing these two means of transfer."}, {'account_id': 9171, 'date': '2014-07-25 07:33:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 1:

commit_message:
Fix seek and tell in BlockingQueue

Currently seek() throws IOError conditionally and tell() returns the
maximum transfer size. This patch fixes these problems.

Change-Id: Ie8bf359457de975a8ae6373a73b5a835e53f2410

commit_message:
Adding documentation for proxy domain usage

Changes
* creating an advanced configuration guide
* adding a link for the advanced config guide to index
* changing the notification config heading to subsection
* adding labels to diskimagebuilder and hadoop-swift documents

Partial-Implements: blueprint edp-swift-trust-authentication
Change-Id: Ie3a3cf0b470ac67670251a5ccd2c3689e338ed1c

commit_message:
Add docs for docstrings in cli to sphinx output

This commit updates the sphinx docs to include the docstrings for the
tempest_lib.cli module to the output from sphinx.

Change-Id: I854e63497836e77a90040bbf1d1a2011a6e873a8

commit_message:
Adds missing db registry api tests for Tasks

The db registry api supports calls to Glance tasks. This patch
adds test coverage to that part of the code.

Fixes bug 1364570

Change-Id: Id7a74239a54d9001c7ac4ab4c8e2b67ac0686125

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-08-21 19:41:35.000000000', 'message': 'Add quotas for Server Groups

Server groups can be used to control the affinity and anti-affinity
scheduling policy for a group of servers (instances).  Whilst this is
a useful mechanism for users such scheduling decisions need to be
balanced by a deployers requirements to make effective use of the
available capacity.

This change adds quota values to constrain the number and size of
server groups a user can create.

Two new quota values are be introduced to limit the number of server
groups and the number of servers in a server group. These will follow
the existing pattern for quotas in that:

* They are defined by config values, which also include the default
  value

* They can be defined per project or per user within a project

* A value of -1 for either quota will be treated as unlimited

* Defaults can be set via the quota groups API

* Values may be changed at any time but will only take effect at the next
  server group or server create.   Reducing the quota will not affect any
  existing groups, but new servers will not be allowed into group
  that have become over quota.

This is part three of a linked sequences of changes that implement the
new quotas - split to make the reviews easier.

This third part implements the quota checks themselves.

Co-Author: Cyril Roelandt (Server Group Quota Unit tests)

Implements: blueprint server-group-quotas
DocImpact

Change-Id: I535c4ac2475d0b0ca6e14081f92e1c7d111792bd

commit_message:
Add quotas for Server Groups (quota checks)

This third change in a sequence that adds new quota values
for server groups, which implements the quota checks.

Co-authored-by: Cyril Roelandt <cyril.roelandt@enovance.com>

Implements: blueprint server-group-quotas
DocImpact

Change-Id: I535c4ac2475d0b0ca6e14081f92e1c7d111792bd

commit_message:
Fixes a Hyper-V list_instances localization issue

The Hyper-V WMI MSVM_ComputerSystem class Caption property can
have different values on various locales. This patch uses a
different query to avoid any localization issue.

Co-Authored-By: Robert Tingirica <rtingirica@cloudbasesolutions.com>
Change-Id: I15103b8edb3ff8934c835826ed00e08593cdeacc
Closes-Bug: #1296478

[{'created': '2014-08-21 19:28:16.000000000', 'message': 'Add quotas for Server Groups

Server groups can be used to control the affinity and anti-affinity
scheduling policy for a group of servers (instances).  Whilst this is
a useful mechanism for users such scheduling decisions need to be
balanced by a deployers requirements to make effective use of the
available capacity.

This change adds quota values to constrain the number and size of
server groups a user can create.

Two new quota values are be introduced to limit the number of server
groups and the number of servers in a server group. These will follow
the existing pattern for quotas in that:

* They are defined by config values, which also include the default
  value

* They can be defined per project or per user within a project

* A value of -1 for either quota will be treated as unlimited

* Defaults can be set via the quota groups API

* Values may be changed at any time but will only take effect at the next
  server group or server create.   Reducing the quota will not affect any
  existing groups, but new servers will not be allowed into group
  that have become over quota.

This is part one of a linked sequences of changes that implement the
new quotas - split to keep make the reviews easier.

This second part adds the new V2 API extension to make the new quota
values visible and changeable.  At this point a Tempest change is
required to get a clean run as it checks for a specific set of
values.

The third part implements the quota checks themselves.

Implements: blueprint server-group-quotas
DocImpact

Change-Id: I78974602d4be04deaf173b3e43f2dab92e8f4171

commit_message:
Add quotas for Server Groups (V2 API change)

This second change in a sequence that adds new quota values
for server groups.  This part adds the new V2 API extensions
to make the new quota values visible and changeable, and updates
the unit tests to check both V2 cases.

Note that Tempest changes https://review.openstack.org/#/c/112474/
is required to get a clean run as it checks for a specific
set of values.

The quota checks themselves are covered in a subsequent
dependent change.

Implements: blueprint server-group-quotas
DocImpact

Change-Id: I78974602d4be04deaf173b3e43f2dab92e8f4171

commit_message:
Move the error check for "brctl addif"

The git commit 873aad92944f8840e772d65eda4b3320d65a9ce7[1] has moved
"brctl addif" command, but the commit did not move its error check.

Now the error check sees the result of "ip addr show dev <interface>
scope global" command wrongly, and the command outputs "Dump was
interrupted and may be inconsistent" sometimes because of a kernel change.
As the result, gate failures happen sometimes.

This patch moves the error check to right place.

[1]: https://github.com/openstack/nova/commit/873aad92944f8840e772d65eda4b3320d

Change-Id: I92ee96e3aa34f7cd154a8ce4b33852b96cabe8c9
Closes-Bug: #1334142
(cherry picked from commit c250696ba12ead71e741cf8f608ce5212b0cc7bb)

commit_message:
Remove second call to get_subnets in delete_subnet

delete_subnet made calls to both get_subnet and _get_subnet,
get_subnet uses _get_subnet so multiple database requests were being
made, this patch removes the call to get_subnet and directly calls
_make_subnet_dict using the result of _get_subnet

Change-Id: I9982821dbb9447e35a4b6e50bc5ad31cec417ca5
Closes-Bug: 1366056

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb

hi, Jeegn Chen and xing:
From your code, it seems that vnx can add a volume to cg directly, am I  right?
storwize support add FlashCopy mapping to cg only. 

So I'm not clear that the cgsnapshot stand for? Xing, Can I get the consistency group spec of the vnx? thanks."}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-05 01:41:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi Li Min,

Yes, VNX supports adding a volume to a CG. 

I just did a search for "IBM snapshot for consistency group" and this link showed up for XIV:

http://publib.boulder.ibm.com/infocenter/ibmxiv/r2/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.ibm.help.xiv.doc%2FGen2%2Fxiv_po_ch05_02.html

So this is the definition for cgsnapshot (snapshot for a cg) from the above link: 

Taking a snapshot for the entire consistency group means that a snapshot is taken for each volume of the consistency group at the same point-in-time. These snapshots are grouped together to represent the volumes of the consistency group at a specific point in time.

So it appears that this concept exists in XIV.  You are saying storwize is different?'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-05 02:01:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

Hi Li Min,

I'm reading the following about Storwize FlashCopy Mapping to CG:

http://pic.dhe.ibm.com/infocenter/storwize/unified_ic/index.jsp?topic=%2Fcom.ibm.storwize.v7000.unified.learning%2Fflashcopy%2Fifs_flashcopy_script.html

So this FlashCopy Mapping to CG is the cgsnapshot in Cinder.      If you don't have an interface to add a volume to a CG on the array directly, it will just be a volume with a CG uuid foreign key, which is already handled by the common code."}, {'account_id': 8587, 'date': '2014-09-05 03:06:31.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 8:

Hi, Xing,
Thanks for your reply, the cg for storwize is a little different from with VNX and XIV, and I will update cg for storwize later, and may need your review and help, thanks.'}, {'account_id': 6491, 'date': '2014-09-05 03:48:27.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 8:

commit_message:
EMC VNX Direct Driver Consistency Group support

Consistency Group support is newly introduced in Juno.

This commit is to add the changes in EMC VNX Direct Driver to
support CG.

Implements: blueprint emc-vnx-direct-driver-cg-support

Change-Id: I6c30ef2609ca8a559f5635129ce6a7c960a9f0a7

commit_message:
QOS edit, create, and delete functionality

This builds on previous patches that adds QOS Spec functionality
to the "Volume Types" tab within the "Admin" -> "Volumes" panel.

Partially Implements: blueprint cinder-qos-specs

commit_message:
QOS Specs - added edit feature

This builds on the new QOS functionality. It adds ability to
edit existing QOS spec key-value pairs

Partially Implements: blueprint cinder-qos-specs

Change-Id: I3b443df168843919ee34f68718ad11f97353bbd4

commit_message:
Set the correct min_disk size when creating volume from image

Sometimes the image min_disk size is specified in a property rather
than the min_disk attribute (for instance, after creating a snapshot
from an instance). This ensures that the correct tooltip and error
message are displayed in these cases too.

Change-Id: I0c7a87a6f00c4cc1a54f8b70e5df9bb1d05de866
Closes-Bug: #1368600

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-04 10:10:28.000000000', 'message': "coraid: fix snapshot deletion

Currently, a request to ESM API for a snapshot deletion looks this way:

{'addr': 'cms',
 'data': {
    'repoName': repository_name,
    'lvName': snapshot_name},
 'op': 'orchStrLunMods',
 'args': 'delClSnap'}

This is correct, however, some versions of the ESM API have a bug that
prevents it from validation this valid request and it fails with:

Must define the new LV name to be assigned to the clone/clSnap.

As a workaround for this bug, provide an 'newLvName' property with a
'noop' value to make the validation pass even on buggy versions.

Fixes bug #1365417

Change-Id: I3fd7f3c6a64cac992735b098368b52b9ab21d85c
"}, {'created': '2014-09-12 07:13:20.000000000', 'message': "coraid: fix snapshot deletion

commit_message:
coraid: fix snapshot deletion

Currently, a request to ESM API for a snapshot deletion looks this way:

{'addr': 'cms',
 'data': {
    'repoName': repository_name,
    'lvName': snapshot_name},
 'op': 'orchStrLunMods',
 'args': 'delClSnap'}

This is correct, however, some versions of the ESM API have a bug that
prevents it from validation this valid request and it fails with:

Must define the new LV name to be assigned to the clone/clSnap.

As a workaround for this bug, provide an 'newLvName' property with a
'noop' value to make the validation pass even on buggy versions.

Fixes bug #1365417

Change-Id: I3fd7f3c6a64cac992735b098368b52b9ab21d85c

commit_message:
Fix using local ID to clean up user/group assignments

When using ID mapping and a user or group is deleted, the mapped id
was being passed to the assignment backend when it's told to clean up
the role assignments for hte user or group. The role assignments are
based on the external ID and not the mapped ID, so the role
assignments wouldn't be cleaned up.

With this change, the external ID is passed to the assignment backend
methods.

Change-Id: I4405329df509f81c9c1178e91092955b16cd586b
Closes-Bug: #1222675

subject: Add characterization test for cleanup role assignments for group

commit_message:
Add characterization test for cleanup role assignments for group

There was no test that showed that when a group is deleted the
role assignments for the group are expected to also be removed.
The test shows that the role assignments are not removed for the
LDAP and KVS assignment backends.

Change-Id: I7a11edcf516740fd2e73f0482ce6bbd67f5ab23f
Partial-Bug: #1366211

subject: Fix LDAP group role assignment listing

commit_message:
Fix LDAP group role assignment listing

The Keystone server would return group assignments as user
assignments when listing roles assignments and configured to use
the LDAP assignment backend.

Change-Id: Icd4f2b7f7f68e8f8b586fd756f7570fd6439e8de
Closes-Bug: #1365787

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-05 16:00:27.000000000', 'message': "Clarify NotFound error when creating trust

If a user creates a stack without the heat_stack_owner role, we
try to create the trust and then fail somewhat cryptically by
letting the NotFound exception from keystoneclient get exposed to
the user.  This is confusing, as it doesn't even mention the role
name (only the ID).

Instead, we can catch the NotFound and propagate a MissingCredential
error, with a list of the role names we need to create the trust.

This error is already correctly mapped to a bad request in the native
API, but not in the CFN exception map, so add it there to avoid 500
errors if this happens via heat-api-cfn.

Now, if a user lacks the required role, they will see an error like:

Missing required credential: roles ['heat_stack_owner']

Which is hopefully somewhat clearer.

Change-Id: Ief4956bdb76ddf0cdb0a642721b63c63b0d007d8
Closes-Bug: #1306665
"}]
commit_message:
Clarify NotFound error when creating trust

If a user creates a stack without the heat_stack_owner role, we
try to create the trust and then fail somewhat cryptically by
letting the NotFound exception from keystoneclient get exposed to
the user.  This is confusing, as it doesn't even mention the role
name (only the ID).

Instead, we can catch the NotFound and propagate a MissingCredential
error, with a list of the role names we need to create the trust.

This error is already correctly mapped to a bad request in the native
API, but not in the CFN exception map, so add it there to avoid 500
errors if this happens via heat-api-cfn.

Now, if a user lacks the required role, they will see an error like:

Missing required credential: roles ['heat_stack_owner']

Which is hopefully somewhat clearer.

Change-Id: Ief4956bdb76ddf0cdb0a642721b63c63b0d007d8
Closes-Bug: #1306665

[{'created': '2014-08-01 19:04:25.000000000', 'message': 'Fix signal handling for WSGI servers

Previously, sending a SIGHUP to the parent process would close the
shared socket used with all the WSGI servers (problematic when multiple
workers are present). Also, exiting the wait loop in the parent would
cause the children to be orphaned. Instead, make the parent process
restart all the children servers upon receipt of SIGHUP. This behavior
seems to make sense given that sending SIGHUP to a child restarts and
creates a new server (due to the parent handling of the children).

Another fix was to issue a SIGTERM upon Ctrl-C in order to not leave
parentless children. SIGTERM was chosen instead of SIGINT simply to
avoid worker tracebacks on the terminal.

Minor unrelated change: the WSGI server in single worker mode has been
changed to also respect the debug flag, exactly the same as with
multiple workers.

Note: the original bug report was examining lack of signal handling
based on the Oslo service code. However, only the engine makes use of
it.

Change-Id: I8519cc6fedf72b38a8ce0762bb86cd70e58e0dc7
Closes-bug: #1276694
'}]
commit_message:
Fix signal handling for WSGI servers

Previously, sending a SIGHUP to the parent process would close the
shared socket used with all the WSGI servers (problematic when multiple
workers are present). Also, exiting the wait loop in the parent would
cause the children to be orphaned. Instead, make the parent process
restart all the children servers upon receipt of SIGHUP. This behavior
seems to make sense given that sending SIGHUP to a child restarts and
creates a new server (due to the parent handling of the children).

Another fix was to issue a SIGTERM upon Ctrl-C in order to not leave
parentless children. SIGTERM was chosen instead of SIGINT simply to
avoid worker tracebacks on the terminal.

Minor unrelated change: the WSGI server in single worker mode has been
changed to also respect the debug flag, exactly the same as with
multiple workers.

Note: the original bug report was examining lack of signal handling
based on the Oslo service code. However, only the engine makes use of
it.

Change-Id: I8519cc6fedf72b38a8ce0762bb86cd70e58e0dc7
Closes-bug: #1276694

commit_message:
Log an error on nfs mount failure

Change from a log warning to a log error when an nfs driver
cannot mount the backend share. Add tests to ensure the error is
logged correctly.

Change-Id: Id9d51aebe349e7a4e09d1211b17efd8d47af97f5

commit_message:
Netapp drivers support for pool-aware scheduling

Adds pools support for all NetApp drivers: eseries, 7mode (iscsi and nfs), and
cmode (iscsi and nfs). With 7mode and cmode drivers, a pool is one-to-one with a
Ontap flexvol. With eseries, a pool is one-to-one with a dynamic disk pool.

DocImpact
Implements: blueprint pool-aware-cinder-scheduler-support-in-netapp-drivers

Change-Id: If5df9de8c3e1ad8faceab4b43c86134dbbc55a51

commit_message:
don't install boto from packages

installing boto from packages pins some other pure python libraries
(like requests) in an unexpected way. As this is pure python we should
instead let this be install from pip and thus be controlled by global
requirements.

Change-Id: If5df9de8c3e1ad8faceab4b43c86134dbbc55a51

commit_message:
Let oslotest manage the six.move setting for mox

This instruction to set up a move in six for the mox module conflicts
with the one in oslotest. We are trying to use mox3 everywhere, so
remove this instruction and let oslotest handle it.

This changeset modifies the tests for the old qpid RPC driver, which is
deprecated. However, we need to make the file importable for testr to
successfully run the tests that aren't deprecated, so we need that
change as well.

Change-Id: I59d5799283233f8411044ddb15c8abfc8850014c

commit_message:
Fixing leaking sessions in 3PAR on attach/detach

Fixed an issue where sessions were not being closed properly
during an attach or detach of a volume.

Closes-Bug: 1367429
Change-Id: Ic7a4ceca855111a8c8a9512fc2d99fcf6df6d79e

Manually update requirements to oslo.messaging

Update requirements for oslo.messaging 1.4 and regenerate config file,
where redis options has been fixed again. It will unblock the global
requirement sync job.

Change-Id: I0d1dc758504e76131738614ccd429171b7c40df1

commit_message:
Unit test for restore with different hosts

This patch adds unit test for restore API with different hosts
for backup and volume.

Change-Id: Ia38ea8f046110c4312212460e7f55ef038e18b93

commit_message:
Fix errors on import with service tags

When skips were added to service tags the CONF check was being
evaluated at import. This will cause an exception when there is
no config file. This commit fixes the issue by moving the config
eval inside the decorator wrapper so that it is only done at run
time.

Change-Id: I4127e2b837e103a8e0c24b324458bee97a2326ec

commit_message:
Delete consistency group failed

Delete CG failed because it compares host@backend with host@backend#pool
(in delete_consistencygroup in volume/manager.py). The fix is to call
extract_host before doing the comparison.

Another issue is about deleting a CG with no host. This will throw exception
when extract_host(group['host']) is called in delete_consistencygroup in
volume/rpcapi.py. The solution is to check the host field in consistencygroup/
api.py and delete it from db there.

Change-Id: Ife28a4f91bd8a4e123c74dac9748ee31cc7b7306
Closes-Bug: #1366205

commit_message:
Set required devstack variables for Ironic+grenade

When sideways migrating from the fake nova driver, do not attempt to
exercise the base side of Grenade using Tempest and Javelin.  Also,
bump the number of VMs enrolled in the Ironic inventory to 3 to
facilitate Tempest concurrency.

Change-Id: I0dc1c1576ff3ff53d1de76af35e6a6f0e2738ac3

Clarify message when no probes are cleared

Log number of probes which were deleted by
using neutron-debug probe-clear
Closes-Bug: #1333103

commit_message:
xenapi: send chunk terminator on subprocess exc

During chunk upload if a subprocess exception is thrown, a malformed
chunk upload occurs.

This patch adds logging for subprocess exceptions and sends the
terminator even in the event of a subprocess exception. The incomplete
file upload will then be cleaned up by the client.

Change-Id: I559f201430bcd4c36d669c7772a10bfe3cd54d41
Closes-Bug: 1365637

commit_message:
Proxy nova baremetal commands to Ironic

This patch will proxy baremetal-node-list and baremetal-node-show
commands to Ironic. All other commands will raise an error if the
compute_driver is set to Ironic, otherwise the api will act as
expected.

Co-authored-by: Lucas Alvares Gomes <lucasagomes@gmail.com>
Change-Id: Id9209d1d34a725750342434fbde1ff5681ff06b8

commit_message:
Test formatting errors with log level being emitted

The test to ensure that formatting errors are handled properly was being
run using info level logging, but the default log configuration for
tests does not emit messages at that level, so switch to error.

Back-ported from commit with the same ID in oslo.log.

Change-Id: Ie11a51deea65627b45a11d7dfca36d16c1b5949e

commit_message:
Exclude sqlalchemy-migrate 0.9.2

Currently, sqalchemy-migrate 0.9.2 is causing failures in
Cinder and Nova.  The proposed solution, for the time-being is
to exclude the version of sqlalchemy-migrate which is causing
these issues.

In order to be able to do this we need to update the
global-requirements.  This change has already been made in
master.

Change-Id: I15ddd031e25ac7a39b8a8fea61e3da42a6bd3ac7
Related-bug: 1368391

commit_message:
Moved preprocess function from base to types

The preprocess function was moved from benchmark.runners
.base to benchmark.types. Decoupling the preprocess
function from base removes a dependency in code.

A unit test for preprocess has also been added to
test_types.py.

Change-Id: I311316c667bb6256ea5f0a32e24328102b62c6e8

commit_message:
Fixes Windows Volume Driver upload volume fails

The copy_volume_to_image requires in some cases an intermediary
conversion, which takes place in the configured image conversion
dir. If this folder is not created, the operation will fail.

This patch ensures that method will create the folder if it does
not exist.

Change-Id: I82b5e76c6d6f3114666f184672667dc3b95bab8b

commit_message:
Remove templates from toctrees

We don't want the templates to show up in the RSS feed, so exclude them
from being converted to HTML and listed in the toctree.

Change-Id: Id3a4086283a0a3983f4f4013a29284ac07c93eaa

commit_message:
Adds CA cert file path option for glance connections

Currently, there is no way to pass CA cert for HTTPS glance
connections. This patch adds new cinder.conf option to enable
secure connection.

Closes-Bug: 1311271
DocImpact - New option added to cinder.conf

Change-Id: I3f39980b94ae314c6351c77f8668ab0922b1c3d8

commit_message:
Add filter to volume transfer REST api

The transfer api supports filter param,
https://github.com/openstack/cinder/blob/master/cinder/transfer/api.py#L72
But the transfer REST api didn't pass the filter params when calling get_all.

Change-Id: I1e29614a3368296571378b4a80a5cfa29b16754e
Closes-bug: 1351084

commit_message:
Improve logging of external events on the compute node

We don't log every event we receive on the compute node, which could
allow some to slip through and look like they were never received. This
patch makes sure to debug log each one so we at least know that it made
it from API to compute.

Change-Id: I817248ea8167be21c55fecad3a39cb45b027596c
Related-bug: #1357476

commit_message:
Add a retry_on_deadlock to reservations_expire

Now that we have an index for the reservations_expire query, we
have uncovered a race with quota usage updates due to the foreign
key on the table, so just retry if there is a deadlock. This is
a fix to unblock the gate while we try to remove the deadlocks
completely.

Change-Id: I1993c3bd1f81facf1d98a4e29f9e8df4858a7d66
Partial-bug: #1350466
(cherry picked from commit 3619c1914e9925e18c062bc11bc3e708137f8322)

This is starting to look good. Here are some notes, some of which I think you are probably aware.

When pulling it up, it doesnt examine the metadata already saved on the aggregate and display in existing.  It should do that and correlate it to the namespace data on the left hand side (so display name shows and description shows).

It isnt doing field validation (integer shouldnt have alphabetic character). List of possible validations are below (based on JSON schema).

When you click into an input field, it should change the description, not just if you click the row.  Otherwise, the description may stay showing whatever row you last clicked even if you are entering date on another row.

When you click on a namespace or object, it isnt showing the namespace description in the description box.

There is a horizontal scrollbar showing on the Available metadata. This needs to go away. I think the whole modal needs to be a bit wider to accommodate larger names.

When entering text in the filter, the tree should expand to the node that matched. Right now it filtering, but staying collapsed. I know that was in original Graffiti widget and I thought that was in the last patch set on this widget.

The header with the filter scrolls.  Is it possible to keep that from scrolling so that a filter can be entered without scrolling back up?

Do we need a confirmation dialog when there are changes being saved?

Somewhere we need to see the actual property name.  Can the first line of the description box show that?'}, {'account_id': 7665, 'date': '2014-07-15 20:26:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9:

Here is the data format from the metadata catalog for the different data types (validation types) for simple properties.

String: http://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/reference/string

"type": "string",
"description": "Property1 blah",
"default": "defaultValue",
"minLength": 1,
"maxLength": 45,
"pattern": "[A-Z]{3}.*"

Integer: http://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/reference/numeric.html

"type": "integer",
"description": "Property2 blah",
"default": 4,
"minimum": 1,
"maximum": 6

Number: http://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/reference/numeric.html


"type": "number",
"description": "Property3 blah",
"default": 4,
"minimum": 1,
"maximum": 6

Boolean: http://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/reference/boolean.html

"type": "boolean",
"description": "Property1 blah",
"default": false

Array:
http://spacetelescope.github.io/understanding-json-schema/reference/array.html

"type": "array",
"description": "Property5 blah",
"default": "NW",
"minItems": 2,
"maxItems":3,
"items":  {
  "type": "string",
  "enum": ["NW", "NE", "SW", "SE"]
},
"additionalItems": False

We used some extra sample data. The UI doesnt handle long names on the left or right side well.  It probably makes sense to widen the widget a bit, but definitely need to handle truncation nicely.  So, if the display name exceeds a certain width, truncate it and change the end to .  For example, Quota: inbound_average Bandwidth may become Quota: inbound_average .  The full name then should show up in the description and / or show up on hover.

Combine the two description boxes into a single one.  Whatever is last clicked (left or right) display in the single combined box.  Davids comment was that right now, you couldnt tell what the description was associated with and it was a little hard to read, since you had to scroll.  The first line could then be Display name (actual property name if property): (newline). For example, Quota: Peak Bandwidth would show:

Thanks for the reviews.  Addressed a number of the comments.  Still need to figure out localization.  Sent out this message a bit ago:

Hi Maxime, et al,

Were working on a widget in angular, and Im not sure how to approach the localization of some partials. Lin and I chatted about this and came up with a working solution, but after some discussion Lin thought it best to check with you to see if there is already an existing solution.  If not, his preference was to just defer the localization for now.

Background:

This page: 
	https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104956/32/horizon/templates/horizon/common/_modal_form_edit_capabilities.html

Specifies this directive: edit-capabilities
	https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104956/32/horizon/static/horizon/js/angular/directives/properties-widget-directive.js

Which in turn loads this partial:
	https://review.openstack.org/#/c/104956/32/horizon/static/horizon/templates/angular/edit_capabilities.html

There are a number of things to localize in the partial, but since angular is doing the loading, it isnt going through server side Django processing with {% trans "My String" }. I tried adding this in (and {% load i18n %}) just to see if it would work, but it didnt.

Am I missing something? Is there a best practice way to do this in Horizon right now?

I was able to use angular DOM manipulation with gettext to replace the String successfully (info below), but Lin thought it might be better to just leave things un-localized in this patch and address this as a bug later when a cleaner, general solution is created for Horizon.  For example, perhaps bringing this library in: http://angular-gettext.rocketeer.be/

For reference, this is what I did with angular DOM manipulation as a workaround:

	Put the following in self.init of the directive:
o	angular.element( '.help_text').html(gettext("You can specify metadata by adding items from the left column to the right column. You could select the metadata added to glance dictionary or you could use the 'Other' option using a key of your choice"));

Thanks for your advice!'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-09 00:41:26.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 33: Verified+1

'}, {'created': '2014-08-05 21:45:23.000000000', 'message': 'Widget to expose the metadata catalog from glance

In Juno, Glance is providing a metadata definitions catalog[1][2] where
users can register the available metadata definitions that can be used
on different types of resources (images, artifacts, volumes, flavors,
aggregates, etc). This includes both simple tags and key / value pairs
(properties, specs, etc).

This widget will get the metadata definitions from Glance
and will let the user add the metadata to the resource being edited.
It provides value validation as well as description information
about the metadata.

An implementation for Flavors is included in this patch. Additional
patches will be made for other resource types.

[1] Approved Glance Juno Spec:
https://github.com/openstack/glance-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/metadata-schema-catalog.rst

[2] Glance PTL Juno Feature Overview:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ptriiw1wK8&t=14m27s

Implements: blueprint tagging

Co-Authored-By: Santiago Baldassin<santiago.b.baldassin@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Skowron <pawel.skowron@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Travis Tripp <travis.tripp@hp.com>

Change-Id: I335d4708f5ce8afe58fb88dbe9efd79e2c04fc9e

and will let the user add the metadata to the resource being edited.

about the metadata.

patches will be made for other resource types.

'}, {'created': '2014-08-26 15:54:40.000000000', 'message': 'Widget to expose the metadata catalog from glance

In Juno, Glance is providing a metadata definitions catalog[1][2] where
users can register the available metadata definitions that can be used
on different types of resources (images, artifacts, volumes, flavors,
aggregates, etc). This includes both simple tags and key / value pairs
(properties, specs, etc).

This widget will get the metadata definitions from Glance
and will let the user add the metadata to the resource being edited.
It provides value validation as well as description information
about the metadata.

An implementation for Images is included in this patch. Additional
patches will be made for other resource types.

This patch also removes Edit Image Custom Properties screen as new
widget provides the same functionality. To avoid regressions owner
property is added to Image Detail screen.

********************** TESTING **************************
You can test this code with Glance patches by following
the instructions at the bottom of this etherpad:
Go to: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/j3-glance-patches
*********************************************************

[1] Approved Glance Juno Spec:
https://github.com/openstack/glance-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/metadata-schema-catalog.rst

[2] Glance PTL Juno Feature Overview:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ptriiw1wK8&t=14m27s

commit_message:
Widget to expose the metadata catalog from glance

In Juno, Glance is providing a metadata definitions catalog[1][2] where
users can register the available metadata definitions that can be used
on different types of resources (images, artifacts, volumes, flavors,
aggregates, etc). This includes both simple tags and key / value pairs
(properties, specs, etc).

This widget will get the metadata definitions from Glance
and will let the user add the metadata to the resource being edited.
It provides value validation as well as description information
about the metadata.

An implementation for Images is included in this patch. Additional
patches will be made for other resource types.

This patch also removes Edit Image Custom Properties screen as new
widget provides the same functionality. To avoid regressions owner
property is added to Image Detail screen.

********************** TESTING **************************
You can test this code with Glance patches by following
the instructions at the bottom of this etherpad:
Go to: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/j3-glance-patches
*********************************************************

[1] Approved Glance Juno Spec:
https://github.com/openstack/glance-specs/blob/master/specs/juno/metadata-schema-catalog.rst

[2] Glance PTL Juno Feature Overview:
https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=3ptriiw1wK8&t=14m27s

Implements: blueprint tagging
DocImpact

Co-Authored-By: Santiago Baldassin <santiago.b.baldassin@intel.com>
Co-Authored-By: Pawel Skowron <pawel.skowron@intel.com>

Agree with Armando's comment.  Added a link to the patch changing the --distributed flag to solve the same problem.

I don't think we need to hold up this patch from merging.  Since Neutron and this client are released on different schedules even controlling when this patch merges will not keep it from being released before Neutron is released or vice-versa.  Also, even after release, we fully expect the new client to be use and work on older versions.  This means that the --ha flag will not be applicable in many cases anyway.  I'm okay with this.

I'd say merge this patch when it is ready and merge the Neutron code when it is ready.  My $0.02"}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-04 03:14:13.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: -Verified

commit_message:
compute: Add standard constants for hypervisor virt types

Introduce a nova/compute/hvtype.py module to serve a similar
role to nova/compute/vm_mode.py, by providing constants for known
hypervisor virtualization types. This is primarily used as second
component of entries in the 'supported_instances' host state
property. It is not to be confused with the hypervisor driver
types.

Related-bug: #1348623
Change-Id: I553697992b010179e2bbf25fb8c0d471a15e4b3e

commit_message:
Clean up documentation

Switch to manually generated rst files for the API documentation so we
do not expose private parts of the library.

Fix formatting of usage.rst

Convert bullet list to section headers to fix rendering issues and make
the docs more readable.

Fix formatting of docstrings in classes exposed in the docs to eliminate
warnings/errors from Sphinx.

Add history.rst

Change-Id: I6f500775f801558f7c0c29f180b60f83a7150e02

prints error message and dies.
On the other hand, devstack also gets error from "neutron net-create"

commit_message:
Update parameter checking with provider network

Currently, devstack can't deploy OpenStack with flat provider network.

devstack checks whether SEGMENTATION_ID is provided or not when it
deploys openstack with provider network. If it is not provided devstack
prints a error message and dies.
On the other hand, devstack also gets an error from "neutron net-create"
command even if it sets SEGMENTATION_ID with flat option.

In addition to that, because neutron allows partial specs these days,
SEGMENTATION_ID checking should be removed completely.

Also, devstack uses PHYSICAL_NETWORK both as "network name" and "physical
network name" in neutron command. If it is not provided, the command fails
to create network. So devstack should check whether PHYSICAL_NETWORK is
provided.

See also:
https://blueprints.launchpad.net/neutron/+spec/provider-network-partial-specs

Change-Id: I2273e3369c688bbce1a6e39b43635b5548cc2b98
Closes-Bug: #1362382

commit_message:
Handle session timeout in the VMware store

The current implementation can lead to session timeouts. This
will occur when accessing the datastore directly through HTTP.
This patch provides a retry mechanism by recreating the session
when getting a 401 status code.

This patch backports Change I54cc9e30c9bc374a2cf82dec4beb9b06594835f8

Change-Id: I245d10c66082215010109e661e799293caec6191

commit_message:
Replace screen_it() with run_process() throughout

run_process will use screen if USE_SCREEN=True (the default),
otherwise it will simply start the requested service. Therefore
wherever screen_it used, run_process can be instead.

Where stop_screen was found it has been replaced with stop_process.

A tail_log function has been added which will tail a logfile in a
screen if USE_SCREEN is True.

lib/template has been updated to reflect the use of the new
functions.

When using sg the quoting in run_process gets very complicated.
To get around this run_process and the functions it calls accepts
an optional third argument. If set it is a group to be used with sg.

Change-Id: Ia3843818014f7c6c7526ef3aa9676bbddb8a85ca

commit_message:
Adds pipeline hints to the example paste config

The order of entries in the pipeline matters. The is especially true for
the application. It must always come last. None of the configuration
documentation for extensions calls this out when they tell the user to
add something to their pipeline.

Change-Id: I46b9b1ac59865d996caa4174867bcf54318035a3
Closes-Bug: #1363932

@Yan:

>This is my first time working with openstack and git reivew.

I'm glad that you decided to start with contribution in rally. I'll try to help you with this patch.

>My original purpose was trying to modify rally-neutron.yaml file by adding those Nova tests to file and have the gate job run with it (Boris asked me to do so)...

Gerrit(git review) provides comfy interface with comments, but such things like "what do your patch doing?" and "why you are trying to change something?" should be written in commit message(you can edit it via gerrit ui).

In your case, imo, commit message should be like:

    add nova scenarios to rally-neutron.yaml

    rally-neutron.yaml should contains more scenarios for better verification
    of neutron.


>I think this is part of because the bug I filed https://bugs.launchpad.net/rally/+bug/1353622

Since you are filed a bug(thanks for it) and your patch related to it, you should add reference to bug in commit message after description of change. 

    Related-Bug: #1353622
or
    Partial-Bug: #1353622

In situation, when your patch fully corrects a bug, you can add:

    Closes-Bug: #1353622

The example of where reference to bug should be left - https://review.openstack.org/#/c/113103/'}, {'account_id': 9545, 'date': '2014-08-10 09:31:12.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

Add nova scenarios to rally-neutron.yaml

rally-neutron.yaml should contains more scenarios for better verification of neutron.

Related-Bug: #1353622

commit_message:
Sahara Cluster and EDP contexts

These contexts will be used to setup Sahara EDP resources before executing
the Job.

The Cluster context will launch a cluster for each tenant.

The EDP context will set up:
* Data Sources for the input and the output
* Job Binaries to run a job from

Note: A refactoring is done to move Sahara contexts under a separate
module.
Note: The contexts do not start any executions.

Change-Id: I8a7420fcc5fc06eaf70a3f1ad4f573a2811ce303

This required me to add some new nova utils methods for
doing a volume attach/detach.

commit_message:
Support multiple heatclient versions for SD

The software_deployment resources lazy loads data via the
heatclient _get() function. Not only is this function private
but the oslo-incubator recently reverted things such that
get() should once again be used for lazy loading details.

See oslo-incubator commit 04a1abe59ac39890f57d2eed57d3d1b12bb5d757

This was merged into heatclient master in:

72017c566850da589f7dc7dc275871986aadbd54

This patch makes it so that heat will work with both versions
of heatclient.

Change-Id: I1799636d39cea410b55ffe72eeecba4f4a7a0f80
Closes-bug: #1308770
(cherry picked from commit a7d782395084c6c16304f17d14b824028c5ba450)

commit_message:
VMware: Implement backup/restore for VMDK driver

Currently, backup-create and backup-restore operations are not
supported for volumes created by the VMDK driver. This change
implements backup_volume and restore_backup APIs for VMDK driver.

DocImpact
    Added a new config option 'vmware_tmp_dir' which specifies
    the directory in Cinder host to use for storing temporary
    virtual disk files during backup/restore.

Implements: blueprint vmdk-backup
Change-Id: Ib19a699f71701c2034e77b8e6b50a8a3295a542b

[{'created': '2014-09-11 09:30:40.000000000', 'message': 'Fix warnings made by keystone_authtoken

auth_* config is deprecated in keystone_authtoken. This change
fixes the log "Configuring admin URI using auth fragments. This
is deprecated, use 'identity_uri' instead." in the gate logs.

The patch also configures auth_uri because keystone_authtoken now
requires it to be set (see the gate log "Configuring auth_uri to point to the
public identity endpoint is required; clients may not be able to
authenticate against an admin endpoint")

Change-Id: I5e067a3e4900e7eb5e0a1230532834e43538145a
'}]
commit_message:
Fix warnings made by keystone_authtoken

auth_* config is deprecated in keystone_authtoken. This change
fixes the log "Configuring admin URI using auth fragments. This
is deprecated, use 'identity_uri' instead." in the gate logs.

The patch also configures auth_uri because keystone_authtoken now
requires it to be set (see the gate log "Configuring auth_uri to point to the
public identity endpoint is required; clients may not be able to
authenticate against an admin endpoint")

Change-Id: I5e067a3e4900e7eb5e0a1230532834e43538145a
