(4 comments)

This looks like a really good change!  There is one error case that I think we should check for that I mentioned inline.  There are also a few places where we could improve the logging, though I'm fine with those either way.

I would also like to see an additional test added that uses an attribute in the RDN that Keystone's mapping doesn't even know or care about.  Something like a 'test_user_id_not_in_dn' test.  For example, configure the mapping like this:

  user_id_attr = uid
  user_name_attr = cn
  ...

Then mock the LDAP search result to represent an entry like this:

  dn: junk=foo,dc=example,dc=com
  objectclass: inetorgperson
  uid: tuser
  cn: Test User
  ...

The test can then do a get_user('tuser') and assert that the 'name' and 'id' values are as expected.

One other good test would be a 'test_user_name_in_dn', which would simulate the way I think Keystone should be configured for Active Directory:

  user_id_attr = sAMAccountName
  user_name_attr = cn

The mocked LDAP entry would look like this:

  dn: cn=Test User,cn=Users,dc=example,dc=com
  ...
  cn: Test User
  sAMAccountName: tuser"}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-09-07 23:53:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 7: Code-Review-1

commit_message:
Use id attribute map for read-only LDAP

For read-only LDAP, we have no control over the DIT. We can only use the
attribute maps. Therefore, we need to honor the attribute map for all
attributes.

This patch also added the missing ID attribute when creating an object in
LDAP. For lookup, we also need the ID attribute to be returned.

Change-Id: I57c099eefdca7e756d294c35cf5b70d119c5c955
closes-bug: #1361306
closes-bug: #1340041

commit_message:
HAProxy stats listener must be set to HTTP mode

The HAProxy configurations defaults section includes "mode tcp", which
results in the stats listener inheriting tcp mode. HAProxy requires
this listener to be set to HTTP mode.

Change-Id: I7e39d5973c3a02f4c66b4758dfd3fb363ac11340

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-09 22:08:37.000000000', 'message': "don't disable usb_tablet if spice agent is enabled

It's not really clear why the usb_tablet, which is a user configurable
field, would be masked by the spice agent being enabled. There are
user bugs about this configuration not providing the usb tablet
support.

We should either change the behavior, or explain why this isn't a
desirable config.

Change-Id: I7945e921b6283519d91e234584d99d9e82218e6d
Closes-Bug: #1356633
"}, {'created': '2014-09-10 10:56:10.000000000', 'message': 'document why we disable usb_tablet in code

This provides a code level explanation for why we disregard the user
option for use_usb_tablet when the spice agent is enabled. It came up
in a bug report, and having the comment close to the code helps carry
the information forward.

Change-Id: I7945e921b6283519d91e234584d99d9e82218e6d
Closes-Bug: #1356633
'}]
commit_message:
document why we disable usb_tablet in code

This provides a code level explanation for why we disregard the user
option for use_usb_tablet when the spice agent is enabled. It came up
in a bug report, and having the comment close to the code helps carry
the information forward.

Change-Id: I7945e921b6283519d91e234584d99d9e82218e6d
Closes-Bug: #1356633

commit_message:
Allow for inclusion of authors and changelog when building docs

When git is available and changelog and author building has not
been turned off try to build these two files so that they can be
included in any subsequent documentation.

Change-Id: I2fc7ade645e3ff1a67e30bd4d35676b5e10916af

commit_message:
Use oslo_debug_helper and remove our own version

With the latest version of oslotest, we can now take advantage
of a common oslo_debug_helper script.
We can now remove our own homebrewed version, minor changes to
tox.ini were needed.

Change-Id: Ifd5d0454e424ecfca0db30d3d3f6350ba7db1b60

commit_message:
Allow new quota types

On Nova commit Ib281e43eabfbd176454bde7f0622d46fb04fcb79, we are adding
two new new quota values for server groups.

However, current Tempest rejects unexpected quota values on its own tests,
and we cannot add the new quota without Tempest changes.

This patch changes quota tests for checking mandatory quota existence
and allowing new quota types.   It also avoids truing to restore the
new quota values for now, until we have client support for them.

Tempest commit I4409a7240dc0a3fa1e11c64c5f5a56ca656b70a4 has already made
the same change for the non admin tests

Change-Id: I618137ea3e8d3d1259c31a2d579c6b752db321e9

commit_message:
[Hbase] Add column for source filter in _get_meter_samples

Earlier column for source was not created and "get_samples"
method with source query worked incorrect. In this change
it is fixed.

Fixes: bug #1330989

Change-Id: Ie8be408d6b54471322e2f585ddf27c50219b8fd3

commit_message:
Fix v2 requests to non-bleeding edge servers

In the case where v2 requests are sent to a server which is not running
head of tree which includes the v2 metadef code some 404 cases need to
be handled to enable standard requests to complete.

This patch aslo improves fetching schemas -- they are now only
fetched as needed.

Change-Id: I8c871f11b909337bd7df19b77e606772dbc634b2
Closes-bug: #1367326

commit_message:
Add documentation for implemented identity meters

Add a list of Identity events they can be metered, specifically:

- user authentication
- project create/update/delete
- role create/update/delete
- user create/update/delete
- group create/update/delete
- trust create/delete

Change-Id: I7a2f25c9e5b64e8f3a2ff986660e5ed531d955c3

commit_message:
Strengthens the regex for mongodb json functions

Encloses function args in quotes. abc: Foo(foo, bar)
changes to abc : "foo, bar". Intent is to prevent
mongodb json peculiarities from preventing parsing
of the json

Change-Id: Iafd81cf74908078155344ef4746632d48c460f6a
Closes-Bug: #1368373

commit_message:
Sync service.py and its dependencies to Cinder

Bug 1362455 made note that our sevice.py was out of sync
from what is currently in oslo-incubator.  We have been syncing
things piece meal.  It would be good to get this code synced up.

----------------------------------------------

Head of oslo-incubator:

commit 820752a10d8277464261661ca211f2c3e7282ce0
Merge: 8ebe497 422e94b
Author: Jenkins <jenkins@review.openstack.org>
Date:   Wed Sep 10 14:14:28 2014 +0000

    Merge "Switch to using pbr's autodoc capability"

-----------------------------------------------

This commit pulls in the following changes listed by file,
ordered from newest to oldest:

cinder/openstack/common/eventlet_backdoor.py
------------------------------------------------
90ae24bf Remove redundant default=None for config options
fcf517d7 Update oslo log messages with translation domains

cinder/openstack/common/jsonutils.py
------------------------------------------------
d9060f69 Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it
ad248f66 Specify namedtuple_as_object=False when using simplejson

cinder/openstack/common/log.py
------------------------------------------------
037dee00 Set stevedore log level to WARN by default

cinder/openstack/common/loopingcall.py
------------------------------------------------
e3773930 Changes calcuation of variable delay
ab5d5f1c Use timestamp in loopingcall
bc48099a Log the function name of looping call
fb4e863c Remove deprecated LoopingCall
fcf517d7 Update oslo log messages with translation domains

cinder/openstack/common/service.py
------------------------------------------------
5f12bba4 Implement stop method in ProcessLauncher
8c00b361 Merge "Remove duplicated "caught" message"
f718e404 Remove duplicated "caught" message
356ecd4d Move notification point to a better place
e2634a75 Add missing _LI for LOG.info in service module
0150ad75 Merge "Reap child processes gracefully if greenlet thread gets killed"
53e1214c notify calling process we are ready to serve
a6fec438 Reap child processes gracefully if greenlet thread gets killed
fcf517d7 Update oslo log messages with translation domains
1e700782 Revert "service: replace eventlet event by threading"
0644073e Simplify launch method
6b4d255e Merge "service: replace eventlet event by threading"
a4f145e4 Merge "Allow configurable ProcessLauncher liveness check"

cinder/openstack/common/threadgroup.py
------------------------------------------------
5a1a0166 Make stop_timers() method public
fdc88831 Add graceful stop function to ThreadGroup.stop
5f8ace05 Merge "threadgroup: use threading rather than greenthread"
2d06d6ca Simple typo correction
4d18b57a threadgroup: use threading rather than greenthread

cinder/openstack/common/systemd.py
-------------------------------------------------
17c4e21e  Fix docstring indentation in systemd
667d1bac Fixed spelling error - occured to occurred
53e1214c notify calling process we are ready to serve

Change-Id: I163f0b80c32c3b8485d9c007fa6e4474494ba31f
Closes-bug: 1362455

commit_message:
Subnets with prefix length 0 are invalid

This patch changes the API behaviour to return a 400 error
when a subnet with /0 prefix length is specified.

This kind of subnet hardly make any sense, and also cannot
possibly work when DHCP is enabled.

Change-Id: I8f822f14b91475dcf86ea44ee607013e61cbb6f7
Closes-Bug: #1362651

commit_message:
Bump up taskflow to its newest version

Taskflow 0.4 was just released so update the bounds
to be the version that is most useful for the juno
release.

Release notes @

https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/TaskFlow-0.4

Change-Id: Ib261d3d3defdb0fa396b0cef16b322bcce00c64d

commit_message:
Use oslo_debug_helper and remove our own version

With the latest version of oslotest, we can now take advantage
of a common oslo_debug_helper script.
We can now remove our own homebrewed version, minor changes to
tox.ini were needed.

Change-Id: Ide72fb3531f0498dfe289d028049cd432aa08887

subject: Allow setting the number of workers to be used.

I'm a bit negative on this, but willing to be out-voted.

It seems like we are already missing things; heat, ceilometer, neutron all have worker options meaning various things.  This is yet-another-flag with fuzzy semantics and name-space; e.g. neutron has an api_workers option that doesn't fit with this, but yet we've got a global "API_WORKERS" variable introduced with this change.  It seems these settings are the type of things that should be globally left to upstream defaults and tweaked locally in localrc as required for various environments

Additional documentation on tips for running devstack in low-memory/high-cpu environments would be a welcome alternative to this IMO'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2014-09-03 09:06:48.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I'm very keen for this to be a devstack setting in localrc; my use case is for a 3rd party CI where devstack-gate only supports localrc and so there is currently no way of setting any maximum number of workers.  In an environment with 6 CPUs (so not even a 'large' number) we have at least 12 workers more than are needed (Tempest runs with a maximum of CPU/2 threads).  Each worker seems to take 3% of 4G (120M) and reducing this number has a notable impact on the memory usage in the CI environment. 

I'd be very open to a name change to restrict the scope, or to expand it to include other workers that you think should be included in this.  Suggestions very much welcome."}, {'account_id': 7118, 'date': '2014-09-03 23:58:16.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

I don't dispute the problem, but I still feel this flag is too abstract about what it is setting (and not setting) and thus is not a good choice for a global.

the devstack-gate scripts have extant pre-test hooks where you could setup local.conf values before the stack.sh run suitable to your environment.  are these not sufficient?  if the underlying problem is an ability to set config options like these easily, we should address that."}, {'account_id': 970, 'date': '2014-09-04 03:43:09.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6:

FWIW, we recently set a default for the Ceilometer workers in https://review.openstack.org/#/c/109058/ to (nproc +1) / 2.  I think this is fine for all worker settings for not-tempest configurations; I'm not sure if Tempest configurations would agree.  So without knowing the answer, my simple proposal is:

 DEFAULT_API_WORKERS=${DEFAULT_API_WORKERS:-$(( ($(nproc) + 1) / 2 ))}

Tempest can override that if necessary, and also if necessary (but only if necessary) we can do:

  iniset ${swift_node_config} DEFAULT workers ${SWIFT_WORKERS:-$DEFAULT_API_WORKERS}

Although I'd rather not as we have more than enough variables to set already...


Also, there is an older review https://review.openstack.org/#/c/95355/ to set workers in Nova."}, {'account_id': 2750, 'date': '2014-09-04 11:32:30.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

There is a real problem here that this fixes. I, for instance, couldn't start a cirros guest on a 3GB vagrant with 2 cpu on my laptop in a live demo because there wasn't 128 M of free memory left after all the python processes were running (and this was devstack default, so no swift, no ceilometer, no trove, no sahara).

I actually think a global dial down is really something we need like this, not just for the xenapi case."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-06 01:27:54.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Verified-1

Merge Failed.

This change was unable to be automatically merged with the current state of the repository. Please rebase your change and upload a new patchset.'}, {'account_id': 1653, 'date': '2014-09-06 07:39:28.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+2

Can you please rebase the code.'}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2014-09-09 01:31:09.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review-1

[1] http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/neutron/tree/neutron/service.py#n41"}, {'account_id': 1131, 'date': '2014-09-09 02:04:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 6: -Code-Review

True, it won't make things worse since the defaults are all 1 worker, I just saw this as a way to make more of these visible.  I'll remove my -1 but it, so maybe others can be done in a follow-up."}, {'account_id': 6486, 'date': '2014-09-09 14:21:32.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6: Code-Review+1

Keystone also supports multiple workers.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2014-09-09 14:54:57.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 7.'}, {'account_id': 6735, 'date': '2014-09-09 14:58:43.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 7:

commit_message:
Allow setting the number of workers to be used.

Environments with large numbers of CPUs will create a large
number of workers which can have an unnecessarily large
impact on memory usage, particular where you know how many
workers are needed.

Change-Id: Ie4bb075310a61a0873c9e56e4974600dbb4794a1

commit_message:
Verify alarm found before modifying

Current behavior is to retrieve alarm by id and conduct operations on the
object.  If the tenant doesn't own the alarm or isn't admin, the user will
receive the message: 'NoneType' object has no attribute 'to_dict'

Above message doesn't provide any useful diagnostic information and indicates a
programming error since an unexpected None-type is encountered and not handled.

This change verifies the alarm is found before using the object.  If alarm not
found it prints the same message for a not found Alarm as other PUT operations
like alarm-state-set:  Alarm not found: <alarm_id>.

This message is more useful for diagnosis and gets rid of the uncaught
None-type error.

Change-Id: I66abcd4498b24ac7cadcf29fe3ced3fcda08458c
Closes-Bug: #1348387

commit_message:
Let oslotest manage the six.move setting for mox

This instruction to set up a move in six for the mox module conflicts
with the one in oslotest. We are trying to use mox3 everywhere, so
remove this instruction and let oslotest handle it.
Imported from the incubator change with the same ID.

Change-Id: I59d5799283233f8411044ddb15c8abfc8850014c

commit_message:
Clarify logging in lockutils

The old logging statements in lockutils made for some confusing log
entries where it would appear a given lock was acquired multiple
times by different threads at the same time.  See referenced bug
for details.

In order to alleviate that confusion, this change does a few things:
1) Adds an explicit "acquired" message inside the lock so it is
   clear when the lock was actually acquired.
2) Moves the release message inside the semaphore so there's no
   chance of it being logged out of order.
3) Removes the "Got semaphore" message and splits it into two
   separate messages depending on whether the semaphore was found
   in the weakref dictionary.  Making it clear which code path
   was followed should help with future debugging.

This is the Nova port of oslo-incubator change
If863c9d3896bc786f3c9c46196ebb0766e57d863

Change-Id: I530befb42a963a40e7d5bf8d4d81fc097e1cb309
Partial-Bug: #1367941

commit_message:
Navigation causes undefined error when clicked on twice

Using the jquery find function on a regular element causes this error. To
resolve this issue, we have to wrap it as a jquery element.

Change-Id: Ibe7dbbdb98c302ca55a30f5205464c469e7d719f
Closes-Bug: #1361315

Updates Example Manifest

The existing example manifest does not work. This patch updates
the example manifest so users can easily deploy Heat using Puppet.

Change-Id: I5b6f19760a7b629e0151f895ab4532af804a8af0

commit_message:
Set Neutron workers according CPU count

In order to improve scalability of neutron-server and
neutron-metadata-agent we need to spawn multiple processes. This patch
changes default of api, rpc and metadata workers according to processors
count on physical machine.

Change-Id: I0480f1652b181e50a8c10230c293d6dfdec3a670

commit_message:
Only delete stack user project from correct domain

Check the domain ID for the project matches the configured domain from
heat.conf, so we avoid the bad outcome of deleting the user's project
when heat has been configured for stack domain users after creating
some stacks.

Change-Id: I247e732033f44daf0de5b0efeff6c263814d13ab
Closes-Bug: #1365332

commit_message:
Support SR-IOV networking in libvirt

This patch takes care of changing the libvirt modules in support of SR-IOV
networking. Added full support in configuring the two VIF types:
VIF_TYPE_802QBH and VIF_TYPE_HW_VEB and in generating the corresponding
domain XML. It also adds support of attaching/detaching SR-IOV ports
on instance suspend/snapshot/resume operations.

Change-Id: Ibc47d13f47fa0b41cefc27bfff942cdbba6eb399
Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-06-09 16:24:30.000000000', 'message': "Support SR-IOV networking in nova compute api and nova neutronv2

Add another member into the requested_network tuple, and the resulting tuple is <net-id, v4-feixed-ip, port-id, pci-request-id>. For a SR-IOV port, Create a PCI request and add the pci-request-id into the tuple. For a non SR-IOV port, the pci-request-id is None.

Add new fields 'profile' and 'vnic_type' in VIF.

Enhance nova neutronv2 api module to:
  -- retrieve a port's vnic-type and the physical network it is attached to
  -- populate binding:profile before updating a neutron port
  -- populate VIF with newly added fields.

Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov

Change-Id: I4aab1cd43960d5b1b54a67a05c191f295dfc46fb

commit_message:
Support SR-IOV networking in nova compute api and nova neutronv2

Add another field into the NetworkRequest object for the request_id.
For a SR-IOV port, Create a PCI request and add the pci-request-id into
the tuple. For a non SR-IOV port, the pci-request-id is None.
Add new fields 'profile' and 'vnic_type' in VIF.
Enhance nova neutronv2 api module to:
  -- retrieve a port's vnic-type and the physical network it is attached to
  -- populate binding:profile before updating a neutron port
  -- populate VIF with newly added fields.
Partially Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov
Change-Id: I4aab1cd43960d5b1b54a67a05c191f295dfc46fb

Perhaps I'm missing some context because there isn't much description of what's going on here. However, this seems to be moving a lot of stuff around all at once, and I'm not sure it all needs to be monolithic.

Further, this seems to be *adding* unversioned and unstructured messaging between (I assume) nova-api and nova-scheduler, which I think goes contrary to some of our goals for versioning everything that goes over the wire.

There is a lot going on here and the umbrella spec for this is huge. Can someone explain what's going on here?"}, {'account_id': 12679, 'date': '2014-08-13 21:02:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 37: Code-Review+1

(1 comment)

A more detailed commit messages is more with my taste.

Been messing with SR-IOV a bit. From my brief exposure to this commit it appears to be supporting libvirt in enabling the iommu to DMA to a SR-IOV virtual function. 

When setting up SR-IOV 'virsh attach-device' passes virtual device information and the VM domain via an xml file.

There seem to be lots of OpenStack documents related to this work as well a a commit that was abandoned. 

IMHO this commit message seems like a reasonable place to provide the big picture, the involved Open-Stack documents, and perhaps an explanation on the previous commit that was abandoned.

'}, {'created': '2014-08-13 23:21:16.000000000', 'message': 'Support SR-IOV networking in the PCI modules

This patch takes care of changing the PCI modules in support of SR-IOV
networking:
  -- Added request_id in the PciDevice object and the corresponding
     model. Migration script is added accordingly.
  -- Added routines to create PCI requests with request id and add
     them to existing requests
  -- Updated pci_whitelist to use devspec that is introduced in this
     patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99043/
  -- stats pool is enhanced so that keys always include product_id and
     vendor_id, and pools are ordered based on the number of
     keys of the pool.

Partially Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov
Change-Id: I9da7bd921f098c958d6fb711a4d03a76862e95c7

'}, {'created': '2014-08-17 03:49:01.000000000', 'message': 'Support SR-IOV networking in the PCI modules

This patch takes care of changing the PCI modules in support of SR-IOV
networking:
  -- Updated pci_whitelist to use devspec that is introduced in this
     patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99043/
  -- For stats pool, to keep the existing behavior, pool keys always
     include product_id and vendor_id. Meanwhile, to work with tags
     and support pci requests based on tags, pools are ordered based
     on the number of keys of the pool. This makes sure that legacy
     pci requests will be satisfied with the pools in the beginning,
     possiblly with devices that are not tagged.

Partially Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov
Change-Id: I9da7bd921f098c958d6fb711a4d03a76862e95c7

commit_message:
Support SR-IOV networking in the PCI modules

This patch takes care of changing the PCI modules in support of SR-IOV
networking:
  -- Updated pci_whitelist to use devspec that is introduced in this
     patch: https://review.openstack.org/#/c/99043/
  -- For stats pool, to keep the existing behavior, pool keys always
     include product_id and vendor_id. Meanwhile, to work with tags
     and support pci requests based on tags, pools are ordered based
     on the number of keys of the pool. This makes sure that legacy
     pci requests will be satisfied with the pools in the beginning,
     possiblly with devices that are not tagged.

Partially Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov
Change-Id: I9da7bd921f098c958d6fb711a4d03a76862e95c7

With the latest change that bumped the version of Instance object, and added the back leveling rule, there are less failures, but there are still about a dozen of tests that failed. In those tests that failed, Incompatible version exceptions occurred. The exception was not caught like in the case of _process_object() in base.py. Thus the failures. 

The reason for that seemed to be that when the compute node (running icehouse with PciDeviceList 1.0) was saving the Instance object, updates that got returned contained PciDeviceList 1.1 (which is incompatible with 1.0). What was supposed to be returned should be 1.0. 

My thinking is 
  - there is still something missing in my change, and  without it, the bumped version 1.1 of PciDeviceList is returned; or
  - there is a bug in the existing code. 

With a lot of investigation, I am leaning towards the latter. This is because in the nova.conductor.manager.object_action() method, to_primitive() is invoked without providing the target version. In the scenario that the compute node is saving the Instance object, the returned update should be converted to the version that is acceptable by the compute node.

One thing that may be worth noting is that in all the tests, PciDeviceList is None. The primitive from the compute node for the save action doesn't contain the field 'pci_devices', but it is added in the updates that is sent back to the compute node."}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-08-16 14:39:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

A correction to my last comments: pci_devices with version 1.0 is part of the primitive from the compute node, but pci_devices with version 1.1 is returned as update.'}, {'account_id': 6685, 'date': '2014-08-16 21:39:53.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 4.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-08-16 21:39:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

I believe the issue with the grenade test was because of the way instance.save() handles pci_devices. Since remotable methods don't go through a backport (since they're already in a given version), refreshing the pci_devices by replacing the ones already on the object with a new set means that new versions get sent back during the return of save() which was causing the issue.

Adding the __ne__ was just defeating the core infrastructure's ability to do what it should have been able to do, had the new versions not been added to the object. See the patch I put in front of this one which works around the problem for now, I think."}, {'account_id': 4393, 'date': '2014-08-23 00:45:57.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 9:

commit_message:
Add request_id in PciDevice

Added request_id in the PciDevice object and the corresponding
model. Migration script is added accordingly. Parent objects's
versions are bumped, and backleveling rules added.

Partially Implements: blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov
Change-Id: I2367339a29c0da8b526fd5105766e51ca4e8c6ab

commit_message:
Replace pci_request flavor storage with proper object usage

This makes the PCI code use the InstancePCIRequests object to store
and retrieve the pci_request information, instead of stashing it in
system_metadata.

Related to blueprint pci-passthrough-sriov

Co-Authored-By: Baodong (Robert) Li <baoli@cisco.com>
Change-Id: I012ee5c118265e044ff41fb58b732728946ee85a

commit_message:
Adds LOG statements in multiprocess API test

Renames _terminate_workers() to _wait_for_workers_to_end() to accurately
match what is done in that method. Adds a bunch of LOG.info() and
LOG.warn() calls in the various methods in the test to get better
debugging information when bug # 1357578 rears its ugly head.

Change-Id: I6698b7c71ec651c812138c8dd93b1e1b33ee1178
Related-bug: #1357578

commit_message:
Sync jsonutils for namedtuple_as_object fix

This is to pull in the fix for bug 1361230 which was introduced
with a prior sync of jsonutils.

strutils is pulled in as a dependency but also fixes an
unrelated bug 1345233.

Changes:

jsonutils
---------
d9060f6 Check for namedtuple_as_object support before using it

strutils
--------
66142c3 Make strutils.mask_password more secure

Change-Id: I9bd2e5f93c2684203487627f64f70d5da7b13586
Closes-Bug: #1361230
Partial-Bug: #1345233

commit_message:
Reuse disable_rollback on stack update

If disable_rollback API parameter is not supplied to stack update,
use corresponding value of existing stack.

Change-Id: Iad60e12d31dc3850071dc0b8562c7b99f53adba4
Closes-Bug: #1324366

commit_message:
Migrate advanced server network to tempest clients

Server is now dict. Changes all related methods accordingly.

Also, moved precondition checks from setUpClass to the appropriate method

Partially-implements: bp:tempest-client-scenarios

Change-Id: I2ad10c3a095b5e326579edfde83d7abcfe077fba

commit_message:
handles keyboard interrupt

When an user intentionally provides an keyboard interrupt, heatclient
throws the entire traceback on to the terminal instead of handling it.

heatclient will now handle the keyboard interrrupt and provides an crisp
message on to the terminal.

Change-Id: Iaa30048e7948d7db1d5b256dd59ca2e0dd842df9
Closes-Bug: #1367283

entries where it would appear a given lock was acquired multiple

commit_message:
Clarify logging in lockutils

The old logging statements in lockutils made for some confusing log
entries where it would appear a given lock was acquired multiple
times by different threads at the same time.  See referenced bug
for details.

In order to alleviate that confusion, this change does a few things:
1) Adds an explicit "acquired" message inside the lock so it is
   clear when the lock was actually acquired.
2) Moves the release message inside the semaphore so there's no
   chance of it being logged out of order.
3) Removes the "Got semaphore" message and splits it into two
   separate messages depending on whether the semaphore was found
   in the weakref dictionary.  Making it clear which code path
   was followed should help with future debugging.

Change-Id: I0fbb473c60d48c9704597d9e3634402857861a66
Closes-Bug: 1367941

commit_message:
Allow FWaaS API test to accept more than one end state

To support distributed routers, it is useful to have this API tempest test
to accept a firewall resource to be either in ACTIVE or CREATED state. After
all, this is not a scenario test, so whether the resoure is actually wired
should be irrelevant.

Closes-bug: #1360351

Change-Id: I2367c2877ca2ebabc08095b33a85659de2b882bd

commit_message:
Big Switch: Retry on 503 errors from backend

Retries requests to the backend controller up to 3
additional times with 3 seconds in between each request
if a 503 service unavailable message was returned.
The scenarios that return 503 messages from floodlight
are normally short lived locks for things like OpenStack
synchronization or upgrade blocks. Retrying should work
in the majority of cases.

Closes-Bug: #1357105
Change-Id: Ifacd3a384cfc797ba6d6af5f3c8649c333473259

commit_message:
Pass kwargs to auth plugins

Auth plugins must sometimes affect the Headers and other portions
of the network setup.  Examples:  Kerberos needs to set the
negotiate header.  X509 to provide the client certificate.

This change makes that capability available to the Auth plugins.

Those plugins will live in separate repositories. There are no
dependent patches for it in this repository.

This was split out by Adam Young from the Kerberos Client patch
written by Jose Castro Leon

Change-Id: Iab7287888e4b3f199b9035c1a24ac43639b5027b

commit_message:
trustor_user_id not available in v2 trust token

The trust information in the v2 token is missing the trustor_user_id
and impersonation values. This means you are unable to tell who gave
you the trust.

Change-Id: I7ed215b3353079d8ed9514c586d256c1226a2c19
Closes-bug: #1331882
DocImpact

The other comments reg. the text of the error, I think your comments are valid but these errors are inside the response body and user doesn't see it on the screen using the client, unless user uses --debug. Hi Srinivas,

Yeap, thanks for the clarification, I forgot about the debug and other commands provided some more error text for me, so I got lost a bit at this point it seems.

As for the text, the REST API can be used without the client also and in general the error message should be well readable. So I'm fine with a shorter version, it was just a quick suggestion, but regardless from the wording please separate the CleintSideError text from the validation error with a colon.

errors and return 400 error with proper message indicating the failure.

commit_message:
Handle invalid JSON filters from the input gracefully

When there is a invalid JSON string on the input for e.g. query-alarm-history
at present the exception raised is un-caught causing a internal error
with a HTTP error 500 returned to the client. This fix will handle those
errors and return 400 error with proper message indicating the failure.

Change-Id: Icd81a88f2c29a8baf7993325bf423435f1ad0924
Closes-Bug: 1366215

commit_message:
Fix config generator to use keystonemiddleware

The auth_token middleware was moved from keystoneclient.middleware
to keystonemiddleware. The config generator is configured to point
to the new location.

Closes-Bug: #1366594
Change-Id: I5543973b2c7ac06c048686c24354ecf6eb251027

commit_message:
update autoscaling example with floating ip for lb pool

this patch updates autoscaling.yaml to (a) require an
external_network_id parameter and (b) to allocate a floating ip address
and associate it with the loadbalancer pool.

it adds a website_url output to make it consisent with some of the other
Wordpress examples.

Change-Id: I2669f51145fc6fbf20da831995acfa17e9291f66

I'm still trying to figure out how this works :)  Need to step through it a bit, can you explain the basic theory of operation here, how your changes implement what you state in the commit message, would speed things along for me at least.  Thanks"}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2014-09-08 14:53:29.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

(3 comments)

Basically what happened with this is I was looking at our object-expired logs and saw that it was sending many deletes to the same container. I saw that if a customer was putting a bunch of objects to the same container with the same x-delete-at time (which happens a lot when people add objects saying delete-after: 1 year) then when the times comes to delete them the expirer would start sending all those deletes at the same time to the same container. This will pull in 100,000 objects and try to distribute the deletes over all the different containers in that set of objects. 100,000 seemed to be enough to solve our problem so I left it at that. 

There are definitely better ways of doing this but the ones i came up with more complicated and I didn't think it was worth it. Also with the sharding of expired containers patch i put in a couple weeks ago this wouldn't be a problem in the future since they would be distributed on the way in."}, {'account_id': 995, 'date': '2014-09-08 15:00:00.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-08 17:32:14.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3: Verified+1

commit_message:
Delete expired objects in slightly smarter way.

When the expirer tries to delete customer objects, if it just walks through the
containers in order the deamon will tend to send DELETEs to the same container
highly concurrently. This will in turn create a lot of asyncs because of all
the concurrent deletes. If the deletes were spread out to multiple containers
it would improve performance and decrease the number of asyncs made.

Change-Id: I3d08118c197b7f18dd7e880bd5664508934ffd24

Cleanup neutron default security groups on tenant deletion

This fix cleanups tenant default security groups that are
automatically created and must be deleted on tenant deletion

Change-Id: Ifcf5ec0391799110f158d113f1b6db8a55a31da9
Closes-Bug: #1283083

commit_message:
Replace confusing member name

Replace the member name 'data' in test_object_slo.py and
test_object_temp_url_negative.py with 'content', because 'data' member
is used as a class member name for the instace of DataGenerator in the parent
BaseObjectTest class.

Change-Id: I24f102531afaffd7e797e588777d4621be7a1084
Closes-bug: #1276835

Do we have an actual use case for needing to provide the override config variable? It seems like the kind of thing that adds a lot of complexity to future support and test matrices.

This seems like the kind of thing we should make a decision on and simply say "you can't do risky things like this with keystone v3"'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 5.'}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5:

Hmm.m. I thought I could mark this work in progress, but can't. Alistair left this as WIP.

The change I made was to add auth_version=v2.0. This *should* allow Tempest tests to work. The logic is that Tempest is probably using usernames; hence should only use v2. If/when Tempest switches to user_ids, we can switch to v3.0"}, {'account_id': 860, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 5: I would prefer that you didn't merge this

The conclusion in bug #1299146, was that as-is, keystoneauth should only be used with v2 -- otherwise you create a potential security hole. And since Devtest uses the sample file, we are in effect telling Tempest what's legal to test.

The use of v2 in the sample conf (here) was meant to be WIP. Ideally, the sequence should be:

1/ Make Tempest use users ids. This is compatible with v2 and v3

2/ Remove the need to specify v2 or v3 in the proxy conf file. This change could then land and Tempest would continue to operate.

I'm reading the Tempest code now to see how to do item 1.

I know Alistair has spent a lot of time thinking about the whole username/domain/ACL issue and I'm not sure I can succinctly explain the logic in a short response. Hence Alistair left this as WIP. However, I know he's interested in getting feedback on whether mandating user-ids with v3 auth is the correct first step."}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 6:

@John re. the override config variable - the use case I had in mind was migrating an existing system from keystone v2 to v3, when there may be existing ACLs using names that would otherwise stop working. Although keystone itself doesn't guarantee globally unique names, I'm led to believe that there are applications in which keystone integrates other means that does provide unique naming, so the operator may be comfortable with using the override to maintain backwards compatibility.

That said, I agree that using the override is potentially storing up a future problem, hence the 'not recommended' comments :) There's a wider discussion to be had around options for migrating to v3, plus the recent policy engine proposal https://review.openstack.org/#/c/89568/ could offer alternatives.

For the time being I need to figure out why this passes SAIO testing but fails on jenkins, so it will be WIP."}, {'account_id': 8871, 'date': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 4:

@Pete, @Guang thanks for your reviews. I will address your comments in next patch.

@Guang re. testing for auth_version == 2 rather than auth_version != 3 : I see your point, but I was concerned that there may be older authtoken versions in deployment - so in _integral_keystone_identity I allow for auth_version="unknown" if neither 'access' nor 'token' are found in token info. Hence I only apply the restriction if we know this is a v3 token, and assume anything else is an earlier version.

So...has 'access' always been in the token info, going back to Diablo or even earlier? Or are there earlier auth versions that will result in auth_version==unknown?'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-05-15 13:22:56.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 9: Workflow-1

@Clay thanks for taking a look, but so sorry it proved frustrating for you :( I've lived with this so long I had forgotten the pain of setting up an environment to exercise these use cases.

The commit message is meant to convey that names in ACLs will still work for users/tenants in the default domain, not just ones that are already there, but newly created ACLs too.

Let me know if I need to make the commit message clearer.

To test out an ID only ACL, you'll need a user/tenant in non-default domain - that'll mean doing a keystone domain-create & sending domain id's to keystone during user-create, project-create. (Oh man, last time i checked keystoneclient CLI itself doesn't support domains, I had to hack my own keystone calls, ... maybe its been updated).

Then, to use those non-default domain user/tenants you'll need to use curl or grab https://review.openstack.org/#/c/91788/ swiftclient patch (which is partly why i was keen to try to get that landed).

I've added something to the commit message as a heads-up - I'm not sure it belongs in the commit message but hey!

Let me know if I can help any more wr.t. keystone config."}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-06-27 14:57:48.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 13.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-06-27 14:57:49.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 13:

@Paul - no worries, there's a lot of history to this ;)

So before this change an ACL such as X-Container-Write: 'devs:alice' would grant access to user with name alice in tenant/project named 'devs'. After the change, that ACL won't work and you would have to use an ACL such as 1234:abcd where 1234 is the UUID of the tenant 'devs' and abcd is the UUID of 'alice'. Thats because there could be more than one user called 'alice' and more than one tenant called 'devs' in multiple v3 domains.

The exception (which is what most of the code deals with) is if 'devs' and 'alice' are both in the default domain, which is where 'legacy' tenants/users end up after migrating to v3. For backwards compatibility this patch still allows 'dev':'alice' in the default domain only, so that any existing ACLs don't just stop working.

As for further work - this patch closes the bug, any other work can be tracked via the blueprint. Consensus seems to be that using names is just a bad idea - users can change their names, but not their IDs.

Perhaps the only safe way would be to resolve names to UUIDs before storing inside Swift i.e. making lookup calls to keystone every time an ACL with a name is set, which could generate significant traffic. OR, create ACLs via a UI which sends IDs to the swift service.

I guess we could open a bug that this feature has been lost, then figure out how to *safely* restore it, but some may argue that the feature was always a bad idea and shouldn't be restored!"}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-08-14 16:58:37.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

Note for reviewers: I am away until September 1st. In my absence I'm happy for Guang Yee, Donagh McCabe or any core to push necessary changes over this in order to progress."}, {'account_id': 7479, 'date': '2014-08-14 17:20:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 15: Code-Review+2'}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-03 12:18:47.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review+1

I just finished my functional tests.

Just one final question before putting my +2 on this.

I can still do something like

swift post -r "tenantname:username" container

and the "tenantname:username" is abled to read from that container (everything in the default domain). Is this still intended or did I misunderstood the commit message? So if someone just uses Swift+Keystone without specifing the keystone version (and is member of the default domain), the behavior is not changing at all?'}, {'account_id': 7847, 'date': '2014-09-09 15:51:46.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15:

(1 comment)

@Christian If you set an ACL 'tenantname:username' for tenant and user both in default domain then that ACL will work IF you have the default keystoneauth config i.e. this patch, by default, does not change behavior in the default domain i.e. this patch should not break behavior of existing default domain tenants/users.

IF you set allow_names_in_acls = False in keystoneuath conf section, then your 'tenantname:username' ACL should not work in any domain. That would be the recommended config for a new cluster, but I cannot make that the default config without breaking existing ACLs in existing clusters."}, {'account_id': 6968, 'date': '2014-09-10 07:18:41.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 15: Code-Review+2 Workflow+1

[{'created': '2014-04-28 20:01:23.000000000', 'message': "Restrict keystone cross-tenant ACLs to IDs

The keystoneauth middleware supports cross-tenant access
control using the syntax <tenant>:<user> in container ACLs,
where <tenant> and <user> may be either a unique id or a
name. The keystone v3 API introduces the notion of domains -
names are unique within domains but no longer globally unique.
The use of unqualified tenant and user names in this ACL
syntax is therefore not 'safe' in a keystone v3 environment,
and we do not believe it is possible to unambiguously express
domain name qualification using the existing syntax.

This patch modifies keystoneauth middleware to detect when an
auth token has been validated against the keystone v3 API, and
if so restrict the cross-tenant ACL matching to use only ids.
(Note that authtoken middleware will only validate a token
against the v3 keystone API if explicity configured to
do so using the option auth_version = v3.0).

A keystoneauth config option is provided for users who wish
to override this behaviour and continue to match names
in ACLs.

This change obviously impacts users accustomed to specifying
cross-tenant ACLs in terms of names, and further work will be
necessary to restore those use cases. Some ideas are
discussed under the bug report. With that caveat, this patch
removes the reported vulnerability when using
swift/keystoneauth with a keystone v3 API.

Closes-Bug:  #1299146

Change-Id: Ib32df093f7450f704127da77ff06b595f57615cb

The keystoneauth middleware supports cross-tenant access
control using the syntax <tenant>:<user> in container ACLs,
where <tenant> and <user> may currently be either a unique

unique within a domain. The use of unqualified tenant and
user names in this ACL syntax is therefore not 'safe' in a
keystone v3 environment.

This patch modifies keystoneauth to restrict cross-tenant
ACL matching to use only ids. For backwards compatibility,
names will still be matched in ACLs when both the requesting
user and the tenant are known to be in the default domain i.e.
the domain to which existing tenants are migrated. However,
names should no longer be used when setting new ACLs in any
account, including new accounts in the default domain.

This change obviously impacts users accustomed to specifying
cross-tenant ACLs in terms of names, and further work will be
necessary to restore those use cases. Some ideas are
discussed under the bug report. With that caveat, this patch
removes the reported vulnerability when using
swift/keystoneauth with a keystone v3 API.

commit_message:
Restrict keystone cross-tenant ACLs to IDs

The keystoneauth middleware supports cross-tenant access
control using the syntax <tenant>:<user> in container ACLs,
where <tenant> and <user> may currently be either a unique
id or a name. As a result of the keystone v3 API introducing
domains, names are no longer globally unique and are only
unique within a domain. The use of unqualified tenant and
user names in this ACL syntax is therefore not 'safe' in a
keystone v3 environment.

This patch modifies keystoneauth to restrict cross-tenant
ACL matching to use only ids for accounts that are not in
the default domain. For backwards compatibility,
names will still be matched in ACLs when both the requesting
user and tenant are known to be in the default domain AND the
account's tenant is also in the default domain (the default
domain being the domain to which existing tenants are
migrated).

Accounts existing prior to this patch are assumed to be for
tenants in the default domain. New accounts created using a
v2 token scoped on the tenant are also assumed to be in the
default domain. New accounts created using a v3 token scoped
on the tenant will learn their domain membership from the
token info. New accounts created using any unscoped token,
(i.e. with a reselleradmin role) will have unknown domain
membership and therefore be assumed to NOT be in the default
domain.

Despite this provision for backwards compatibility, names
must no longer be used when setting new ACLs in any account,
including new accounts in the default domain.

This change obviously impacts users accustomed to specifying
cross-tenant ACLs in terms of names, and further work will be
necessary to restore those use cases. Some ideas are
discussed under the bug report. With that caveat, this patch
removes the reported vulnerability when using
swift/keystoneauth with a keystone v3 API.

Note: to observe the new 'restricted' behaviour you will need
to setup keystone user(s) and tenant(s) in a non-default domain
and set auth_version = v3.0 in the auth_token middleware config
section of proxy-server.conf. You may also benefit from the
keystone v3 enabled swiftclient patch under review here:
https://review.openstack.org/#/c/91788/

DocImpact

blueprint keystone-v3-support

Closes-Bug:  #1299146

Change-Id: Ib32df093f7450f704127da77ff06b595f57615cb

I'm really wondering why this wasn't covered by the existing tests, since there is already a check for a 400 return code. Am I missing something here?"}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-09-09 17:11:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

The existing test passed.  However when using a real proxy server, the proxy server catches all exceptions before returning to the middleware.  So instead of the middleware catching it (as the unit test does), the proxy server sees the EOFError and thinks that it was a client disconnect.

So, instead of returning a HTTP 400: FormPost: max_file_size exceeded, it returns a HTTP 499: Client Disconnect.'}, {'account_id': 7433, 'date': '2014-09-09 17:16:04.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

commit_message:
Fix FormPOST max_file_size exceeded bug.

When using FormPOST, if the size of the file being posted exceeds
max_file_size, a HTTP 499 was being returned rather than HTTP 400.

Change-Id: I48c781735c66eccde3deb6f9c3c184aee964a4a5

commit_message:
Have the EC2 instance test to wait for termination

Several EC2 test did not waited for instance termination.
This change adds an explicit wait for termination,
for the test cases which wants to terminate
the instance inside the test case.

The #1365831 happened because the 'test_run_terminate_instance',
did not waited for the final termination.

Change-Id: Icd3b86ebc8464bd20319e8582541d78fded10ee2
Closes-Bug: #1365831

commit_message:
ceilometer spamming syslog

regression in code which causes ceilometer to spam syslog. this
patch explicitly configures log_level in ceilometer swift
middleware as we no longer rely on swift middleware logic to
configure it.

Change-Id: I248040cb1d842cf89ed32ef28d8575012d36e08f
Closes-Bug: #1367880

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-11 11:56:29.000000000', 'message': "Update oslo log module

Changes -
 * Set stevedore log level to WARN by default
 * Add unicode coercion of logged messages to ContextFormatter
 * Correct coercion of logged message to unicode
 * Except socket.error if syslog isn't running
 * Fix E126 pep8 errors
 * Set keystonemiddleware and routes.middleware to log on WARN level
 * Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for
 * Make logging_context_format_string optional in log.set_defaults
 * Add default log level for websocket

Change-Id: Ib0529a52c1b6f6328b1022c4a61da752258d01f9
"}]
commit_message:
Update oslo log module

Changes -
 * Set stevedore log level to WARN by default
 * Add unicode coercion of logged messages to ContextFormatter
 * Correct coercion of logged message to unicode
 * Except socket.error if syslog isn't running
 * Fix E126 pep8 errors
 * Set keystonemiddleware and routes.middleware to log on WARN level
 * Adjust oslo logging to provide adapter is enabled for
 * Make logging_context_format_string optional in log.set_defaults
 * Add default log level for websocket

Change-Id: Ib0529a52c1b6f6328b1022c4a61da752258d01f9

commit_message:
Add oslo.serialization

Add the new Oslo library for managing object serialization. This code is
moving out of the incubator into a library, so projects that wish to
continue using it need the requirement added to the global list first.

NOTE: this is needed for clients installed from master using oslo.serialization.

Conflicts:
	global-requirements.txt

Partial-Bug: #1366748

Change-Id: Iff29ce2e88cddc2332229cfbbc518251dd2c76f3
(cherry picked from commit 2ce3f8259b56410bdd73deca09b7963f4a46e1da)

commit_message:
Stop using intersphinx

Remove intersphinx from the docs build as it triggers network calls that
occasionally fail, and we don't really use intersphinx (links other
sphinx documents out on the internet)

This also removes the requirement for internet access during docs build.

This causes docs jobs to fail because we error out on warnings.

Change-Id: I71e941e2a639641a662a163c682eb86d51de42fb
Related-Bug: #1368910

commit_message:
VolumeMultiBackendTest: delete error volumes

Record the volume ID before waiting for the volume status to go
available. This means that if the volume goes into error the tearDown
method can remove the volume.

Change-Id: I67e74af999862fc37c4f5b2474b50b62cce328e9
Partial-Bug: #1352498

commit_message:
state the fact that NSX Service node is mandatory for Mirantis OpenStack

- NSX cluster can successfully operate without Service node, but our
  tests show that creation of virtual interfaces fails, due to incorrect
  configuration of `replication_mode' setting in Neutron NSX plugin
  confguration file (plugin is configured to use Service node)
- we need more work to be done to implement working Mirantis OpenStack
  with NSX cluster that operates without Service node
- note that OpenStack itself can be used with NSX cluster that lacks
  Service node
- while here add missing article

Change-Id: Ibd88834a525104f4c9e71c355c3e7e0ea833adba
Closes-bug: #1365043

commit_message:
Adds "alarm-history" to test_telemetry_alarming_api

This submission is to verify alarm-history functionality
and also added required supporting function in
telemetry_client_base.py script.

commit_message:
Fix selection of vsphere as non default backend

When vsphere is not the default backend, selecting
a specific backend over the documented "--store vsphere"
option does not work, since there is a class name check
that checks for vmware_datastore (as that is the name
of the class). However that class only handles the scheme
vmware_datastore. Add an alias hack similar to how
filesystem is handled.

Change-Id: Ifa2922b19f50b978e4ed1a2bf21663163ef8c58d
Fixes-Bug: #1354261

commit_message:
ResourceGroup build from list of resource names

This changes ResourceGroup internal implementation to be driven by
a list of resource names rather than a count of resources.

This maintains the current behaviour of sequential number resource
names, while allowing subclasses to choose a completely different
resource name scheme.

Change-Id: I17d046155f8d830ced789ede6a969ac4f125576d
Partial-Blueprint: deployment-multiple-servers

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-09-05 23:14:12.000000000', 'message': "WIP: Reactivating materialized theory tests

One of the features we mothballed before the alpha was
the option to use a theory that explicitly stores the contents
of all tables that are defined via rules.

This change begins reactivating that option
by reactivating the code's tests.

This is a WIP mainly because there's a bug in the theory when
rules get inserted/deleted.  If rules are inserted/deleted
in the same chunk of events that some of the dependent data
is updated, we do not get the right answer.  The reason is
that we are computing the collection of data generated
by the rule when that rule is enqueued, but that event
happens before the queue is processed.  Example..

insert[q(1)]
insert[p(x) :- q(x)].
enqueue[q(1)]
compute-consequences[p(x) :- q(x)] = {}
enqueue[p(x) :- q(x)]
enqueue[{}]
process[q(1)] <- when q(1) actually gets inserted
process[p(x) :- q(x)] <- just inserts rule

Clearly we need to do the data computation at the processing
step instead of at the enqueueing step.

Change-Id: I6f9ee25050d6c6cd42e176335d83b6fb7ac2821d

commit_message:
Reactivating materialized theory tests

One of the features we mothballed before the alpha was
the option to use a theory that explicitly stores the contents
of all tables that are defined via rules.

This change begins reactivating that option
by reactivating the code's tests.

Change-Id: I6f9ee25050d6c6cd42e176335d83b6fb7ac2821d

commit_message:
Resurrected more policy tests

Before the alpha release, we mothballed a number of policy tests and features.
We thought we had saved all the tests for features that were
actually included in the alpha, but we missed some.

This change reactivates those tests.

Change-Id: I42f3ea01d8cb07204321d229de864db43f492c66

commit_message:
Enable filtering of services by name

This commit enables the filtering of services through the service's
name. This wasn't available before, since the name is not saved in the
backend as a column, but instead it's stored as an extra attribute.

Thus, this commits enables this type of search by asserting a TODO that
was left in the SQL backend, and also adding the `name` attribute to the
filterprotected decorator.

This is needed since some clients (namely python-openstackclient) assume
that this functionality already exists and thus give the option to
create endpoints with the service name as a parameter.

Change-Id: Ifc9c1e44e908410740f6f20380b264d35096fcac
Closes-Bug: #1350273

passwords.

commit_message:
Make generate_password more secure

It appears that the generate_password function in
cinder/volume/utils.py was based on a function from
nova/utils.py .  The version in Nova has been updated
to use random.SystemRandom() to get better random
passwords.

This change brings those changes into Cinder.

NOTE: In the future we should look at getting this function
      moved to Oslo as it is being used in Cinder and Nova.

Change-Id: I3ea4fffbcbf22d7e0de4874dcfb592ecf523b4cc
Closes-bug: 1368040

commit_message:
Add merge_stderr option to all client methods

This commit makes the client methods behave more uniformly. Before
there only certain methods had a kwarg for merge_stderr, which could
lead to unexpected behavior depending on the clients being used. By
adding the option everywhere there shouldn't be an unexpected behavior
around merge_stderr.

Change-Id: I227d5e684c94da29a47eb9876a9ed40cdbea084c

The current docs are wildly out of date, and need to be updated
to actually show what are valid sections in keystone.conf

commit_message:
Fix the filename copy into the filename input

In horizon/static/horizon/js/horizon.form.js,
edited the function handle_object_upload_source.

As the form validation is done by Angular,
the filename change has to be done by Angular (done).
The filename input has to be filled if it has been emptied
(added a condition in the if statement).

Now, when you choose a file, its filename in copied into the filename input
each time you choose a new file and until you manually
change the filename input content.

Change-Id: Ibbebc7ecf2902486db24f50ba12d20facf258581
Closes-Bug: 1364295
Co-Authored-By: Maxime Vidori <maxime.vidori@enovance.com>

[{'created': '2014-09-10 19:42:55.000000000', 'message': 'Fixed bug for inserting rules via API

Previously, if you inserted multiple rules in a single string
via the API, we did not catch the error.  Instead, we simply
processed the first rule.  One symptom of this problem
is an internal server error when someone uses a minus sign
in the middle of a table name, e.g. router-name(x) :- ...
Because of the grammar, this rule would be parsed as two
separate rules: router-() and name(x) :- ...

This change checks that the number of rules sent into
the API is always 1 and shows you the list of rules that
you submitted in the error message.  This helps the user
debug the problem.

Perhaps the grammar should be changed as well, but this
fix is necessary in either case.

Closes-bug: 1367887

'}]
commit_message:
Fixed bug for inserting rules via API

Previously, if you inserted multiple rules in a single string
via the API, we did not catch the error.  Instead, we simply
processed the first rule.  One symptom of this problem
is an internal server error when someone uses a minus sign
in the middle of a table name, e.g. router-name(x) :- ...
Because of the grammar, this rule would be parsed as two
separate rules: router-() and name(x) :- ...

This change checks that the number of rules sent into
the API is always 1 and shows you the list of rules that
you submitted in the error message.  This helps the user
debug the problem.

Perhaps the grammar should be changed as well, but this
fix is necessary in either case.

Closes-bug: 1367887
Change-Id: I7efec72ef96d6958c1af227d3ef8fb0707703f3b

commit_message:
Updating JobBinaries to use proxy for Swift access

Changes
* refactoring get_raw_binary to accept proxy configs
* refactoring get_raw_data to use proxy Swift connection when necessary
* adding function to get a Swift Connection object from proxy user
* refactoring upload_job_files_to_hdfs and upload_job_files to use proxy
  user when necessary
* changing JobBinary JSON schema to allow blank username/password if
  proxy domains are being used
* adding function to get the Swift public endpoint for the current
  project
* adding test for JobBinary creation without credentials

Partial-implements: blueprint edp-swift-trust-authentication
Change-Id: I02e76016194fbbb62b8ab7b304eecc53d580a79c

commit_message:
Compute v2 api server status value cleanup

Server status need to be updated to reflect current standards.
Adding statuses like STOPPED, PAUSED, SOFT_DELETED and updating
old values to new ones like RESCUED, RESIZED, DELETED.

No, they are not used on Windows (yet -- a project for another day). They are used on Linux and Mac OS X if you choose to install using VirtualBox guest-additions (instead of over ssh). Change-Id: I7716528c02aa4f8b5fc0901ff91ba5d37b5a0d9f

commit_message:
labs: split out process_begin_files

Move the processing of *.begin status files into a separate function.
Call that function only if the host's status directory is shared with
the client scripts (through VirtualBox guest-additions).

Change-Id: I7716528c02aa4f8b5fc0901ff91ba5d37b5a0d9f

For dse to use eventlets rather than threads

This spec proposes a change to Congress and the DSE to make
the DSE use greenthreads rather than regular threads.

Change-Id: If2ea9a54982c602e60dfda0cfc0852224846e876

commit_message:
Update scripts to initialize heat domain

Updates devtest_{seed,undercloud,overcloud} to use Heat's tool for
creating a stack user domain in Keystone.

Updates the passwords scripts and passwords rc files as well to account
for the additional password.

This depends on If4b4266ce66212d7ae2579e7da6d3bae779ad04a landing in
Heat.

Partial-Bug: #1287453
Change-Id: I5ff23caab9f87baf96007b61b3bd604694f44301
Co-Authored-By: Clint Byrum <clint@fewbar.com>

commit_message:
Ironic:  Fix direct use of flavor and instance module objects

This replaces all uses of nova.objects.flavor_obj.Flavor* with
nova.objects.Flavor* and nova.objects.instance_obj.Instance* with
nova.objects.Instance*

This work was done throughout Nova. An example of this is
commit 3c1085f528596089a638ac3bb44a9ed3e201e62f.

Change-Id: I8f2dbb408acbdf8124bc141925de03ce6f12bd91

Add heat-keystone-setup-domain to sphinx conf.py

The man page for heat-keystone-setup-domain was not being generated
because it was not included in the sphinx conf.py.

Change-Id: Ic1c2025fc7f61e3c37906b42bd84e1df893920fc

Yeah I know this hasn't fixed the issue yet, that's why I added the debug statements to handle_lifecycle_event and stop_instance after acquiring the instance lock so we can see if we're doing some redundant operations here and we can short-circuit, like if the instance is already powered-off/stopped when stop_instance is called, then we should just detect that, log and return.

WIP since I have to dig through the logs a bit."}, {'account_id': 4690, 'date': '2014-07-19 18:58:18.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

Understood, I was trying to help by digging through the logs and posting shortcut links to the errors in case it might save you time.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-07-25 18:42:01.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 2:

@Melanie, thanks for looking, I'm just getting back to this today.

I checked logstash on this change and the original UnexpectedTaskStateError and it doesn't show up anywhere in patch set 2:

message:"UnexpectedTaskStateError: Unexpected task state: expecting (u'powering-off',) but the actual state is None" AND tags:"screen-n-cpu.txt" AND build_change:108014

http://logstash.openstack.org/#

From looking at what you found, the sync block maybe moved the race to a different location?

http://logs.openstack.org/14/108014/2/check/check-tempest-dsvm-full/a7ed28e/logs/screen-n-cpu.txt.gz?level=TRACE#_2014-07-18_19_54_15_849

It looks like whenever stop_instance is called on 3885be2e-0074-45f5-8111-31c80f954460 it's in vm_state:active, task_state:powering-off and power_state:1 (running), so those are normal.

The trace is a bit odd, because we're hitting _sync_instance_power_state and the task_state is None at that time, but the vm_state is STOPPED and the power_state must be 1 (running), so the compute manager calls the force_stop API which expects there to be no task_state but there is when the compute API runs, maybe because the lock in the periodic task is let go and something else acquires it to change state.

Maybe the periodic task should be doing a call rather than a cast to compute_api.force_stop so that it's sure of the state by the time it comes back.

If we did that the call to compute.manager.stop_instance should be OK because the compute_api.force_stop will set the task_state to 'powering-off' which is what stop_instance checks for in the manager.

If we hit a new race in stop_instance, then I think we need to refresh the instance from the database (like _sync_instance_power_state does) and if the instance is stopped and the power_state is 4 (shutdown), then we just log it and return.'}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-07-25 18:45:42.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 2:

Alternatively we could just catch UnexpectedTaskStateError in _sync_instance_power_state and basically not trace on it, just say 'oops, something is racing here, ignore and move on'."}, {'account_id': 6873, 'date': '2014-07-25 19:00:17.000000000', 'content': 'Uploaded patch set 3.'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-07-25 19:00:20.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 3:

revisions:
[{'created': '2014-07-18 13:58:45.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: synchronize handle_lifecycle_event to avoid stop race error

Commit cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 added locks to
stop_instance and the _sync_power_states periodic task to try and fix a
race between stopping the instance via the API where the task_state is
set to powering-off, and the periodic task seeing the instance
power_state as shutdown in _sync_instance_power_state and calling the
stop API again, at which point the task_state is already None from the
first stop API call and we get an UnexpectedTaskStateError.

That change missed the call to _sync_instance_power_state in
handle_lifecycle_event which is also detecting power state changes via
events and automatically stopping the instance, which also races with
stop_instance, so this change adds the lock to handle_lifecycle_event
also.

Closes-Bug: #1339235
Closes-Bug: #1266611
Related-Bug: #1320628

Change-Id: Ib495a5ab15de88051c5fa7abfb58a5445691dcad
'}, {'created': '2014-07-18 17:39:11.000000000', 'message': 'WIP: synchronize handle_lifecycle_event to avoid stop race error

That change missed the call to _sync_instance_power_state in

Adds debug logging to handle_lifecycle_event and stop_instance to

Closes-Bug: #1339235

'}, {'created': '2014-07-25 19:00:17.000000000', 'message': "WIP: synchronize handle_lifecycle_event to avoid stop race error

Commit cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 added locks to
stop_instance and the _sync_power_states periodic task to try and fix a
race between stopping the instance via the API where the task_state is
set to powering-off, and the periodic task seeing the instance
power_state as shutdown in _sync_instance_power_state and calling the
stop API again, at which point the task_state is already None from the

That change missed the call to _sync_instance_power_state in
handle_lifecycle_event which is also detecting power state changes via

also.

Adds debug logging to handle_lifecycle_event and stop_instance to
dump the current instance state after acquiring the lock.

Also adds a check for UnexpectedTaskStateError when the sync instance
power state method calls compute_api.force_stop since it's an
asynchronous call so we can still get that error, but it shouldn't
stacktrace since the sync method should basically ignore anything
going through a task state change.

Closes-Bug: #1339235
Closes-Bug: #1266611
Related-Bug: #1320628

Change-Id: Ib495a5ab15de88051c5fa7abfb58a5445691dcad

"}, {'created': '2014-07-30 06:20:03.000000000', 'message': "Stop stack tracing when trying to auto-stop a stopped instance

Commit cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 added locks to
stop_instance and the _sync_power_states periodic task to try and fix a
race between stopping the instance via the API where the task_state is
set to powering-off, and the periodic task seeing the instance
power_state as shutdown in _sync_instance_power_state and calling the
stop API again, at which point the task_state is already None from the
first stop API call and we get an UnexpectedTaskStateError.

The handle_lifecycle_event method is getting callbacks from the libvirt
driver on state changes on the VM and calling the
_sync_instance_power_state method which may try to stop the instance
asynchronously, and lead to UnexpectedTaskStateError if the instance is
already stopped by the time it gets the lock and the task_state has
changed.

so this change adds logic to stop_instance such that if the instance
says it's active but the virt driver says it's not running, then we add

rather than a cast when _sync_instance_power_state calls the stop API
but in some previous testing it doesn't appear to make a significant
difference in the race found when we hit the stop_instance method.

commit_message:
Stop stack tracing when trying to auto-stop a stopped instance

Commit cc5388bbe81aba635fb757e202d860aeed98f3e8 added locks to
stop_instance and the _sync_power_states periodic task to try and fix a
race between stopping the instance via the API where the task_state is
set to powering-off, and the periodic task seeing the instance
power_state as shutdown in _sync_instance_power_state and calling the
stop API again, at which point the task_state is already None from the
first stop API call and we get an UnexpectedTaskStateError.

The handle_lifecycle_event method is getting callbacks from the libvirt
driver on state changes on the VM and calling the
_sync_instance_power_state method which may try to stop the instance
asynchronously, and lead to UnexpectedTaskStateError if the instance is
already stopped by the time it gets the lock and the task_state has
changed.

Attempting to lock in handle_lifecycle_event just moves the race around
so this change adds logic to stop_instance such that if the instance
says it's active but the virt driver says it's not running, then we add
None to the expected_task_state so we don't stacktrace on
instance.save().

An alternative and/or additional change to this would be doing a call
rather than a cast when _sync_instance_power_state calls the stop API
but in some previous testing it doesn't appear to make a significant
difference in the race found when we hit the stop_instance method.

Adds a bunch of debug logging since this code is inherently racey and
is needed when looking at failures around these operations.

Closes-Bug: #1339235
Closes-Bug: #1266611
Related-Bug: #1320628

Change-Id: Ib495a5ab15de88051c5fa7abfb58a5445691dcad

so locally, when running with fedora 20, mariadb 5.5, to load 4753 samples (35 meters, 100 res) using a tweaked make_test_data.py (adds metadata and multiple meters/resources), i get:

   - master: ~1m24.500s (little variance)
   - normalised patch: ~1m21.500s (with a bit of variance, min: 1m19.407s, max:1m22.300s)
   - normlised+sqla-core: ~1m14.590s

adding Mike Bayer to see if patch is advisable.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-02 21:39:45.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

I'm not sure what your timing is but I'm working out ORM patterns that would allow comparable improvements to be available on that side of things.   in particular the "baked query" idea at https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/OpenStack_and_SQLAlchemy#Baked_Queries would add caching to the construction of that SELECT that would make it actually faster, and the construction of the insert() queries are already cached when using the unit of work, functionality that will be present when I finish up the fast object save feature at https://bitbucket.org/zzzeek/sqlalchemy/issue/3100.

also the sqlite stuff here shouldn't be necessary anymore, im not sure if this is using oslo.db but we've solved that "no savepoint" issue over there.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-02 21:58:38.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

oh I didn't even see the "1m" in there, so the time is 1m 24s down to 1m 15s?   e.g. 10%.  that's actually not very compelling!  I would have expected it to be better than that.

35 meters and 100 resources is nothing, then for 4700 rows you have to do a full from-scratch load of those every time on a per-row basis.  1m24s to do only 4700 of anything is really slow.  I really think this would be *way* faster if the means of operation were changed:

1. you got that caching in

2. heck, even used a stored procedure for the three rows here

3. the API batched inserts using a queueing system.  Even the ORM can insert 4700 rows in less than a second if you pass them all in at once.   The transaction boundary being run 4700 times, not even including two savepoints within it, is also taking up a ton of time (mysql isn't fast at this).

That the switching ORM for Core only gives you 10% should prove that's not where the main issue lies.'}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-02 22:00:58.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

hey gordon, if you can produce Python profiling files (see http://docs.sqlalchemy.org/en/rel_0_9/faq.html#code-profiling) we can run them into runsnake (http://www.vrplumber.com/programming/runsnakerun/) to reason about where the slowness is.'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-02 22:25:35.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23:

redo: http://paste.openstack.org/show/104991/'}, {'account_id': 3012, 'date': '2014-09-03 12:17:24.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 23: Code-Review+1'}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-03 14:28:44.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

thanks for the suggestions Mike, i think the caching idea is really interesting but we concluded it's outside the scope of Juno.

regarding batch inserts... it might be a bit too big for this cycle as well but how exactly does batch inserts work in a multi-worker environment and get-or-create logic? it seems like there'd be a lot of rollback?"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-03 14:36:02.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

when you have the batches, you can pre-select the full batch of items you expect to be using, so you dont have to select per-item.  Also, if the batches are being processed serially, you wont have a need for detecting collisions as you're working in serial.  Tasks can be run in parallel by sending out different resource/meter combinations to  workers on a deterministic basis using something like consistent hashing - each subprocess again won't have any chance of collisions with this approach but you still can process huge numbers of items very fast.

this is how you actually scale this thing.  nipping at database abstraction layers is not really where the issue lies, if only I can convince nova of this also ... :)"}, {'account_id': 11816, 'date': '2014-09-03 14:37:45.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

ding - in your profile, confirmed the main expenditure is the number of MySQL transactions:

4753   53.946    0.011   53.946    0.011 {method 'commit' of '_mysql.connection' objects}

the vast majority of time here is being spent committing MySQL transactions.  So batching is the only way this code will ever run in a performant style."}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-03 19:26:54.000000000', 'content': "Patch Set 23:

thanks for the explanation Mike. i had a feeling it would require some level of task/group management to properly distribute writes without hitting a deadlock situation with batch writes... it'd be a pretty large change from the current concept of dumb workers just pulling samples as they arrive and pushing them to db.

i'll continue digging to see if there's a quick fix for what matches ceilometer's current use case"}, {'account_id': 6537, 'date': '2014-09-04 14:46:03.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Patch Set 23 was rebased'}, {'account_id': 3, 'date': '2014-09-04 21:48:51.000000000', 'content': 'Patch Set 24: Verified-1

commit_message:
switch to sqlalchemy core

ORM has an overhead associated with it. we need fast writes so
switch to use sqlalchemy core to improve performance.

Closes-Bug: #1356000
Change-Id: I45c76d4f294f9bdb6d0f04e94d4be7e0f7ca6f2a

commit_message:
Add use of nova_kwargs for nova servers create to improve readability

so if we have to add new args to the servers.create call,
we'll be able to use nova_kwargs and avoid mulitple calls
of servers.create with multiple if conditions.

Closes-Bug: 1368109
Change-Id: Ib2e435846d3f3d6907c4959ba31abf003c3b47d7

[{'created': '2014-09-11 18:52:34.000000000', 'message': 'Fix password leak from ProcessExecution errors

This backport the necessary changes to fix both issues:
* Make execute method clean password in exeception
* Make sure mask_password works properly

The backport is not trivial as these fix relies on many other changes,
only the necesasry code have been imported/adapted.

------------------------------------------------
The sync pulls in the following changes (newest to oldest):

6a60f842 - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages (ssh)
63c99a0f - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages
66142c34 - Make strutils.mask_password more secure
d6b55fb2 - Remove `processutils` dependency on `log`
cb5a804b - Move `mask_password` to strutils

-----------------------------------------------

Closes-Bug: 1343604
Closes-Bug: 1345233
SecurityImpact

commit_message:
Fix password leak from ProcessExecution errors

This backport required changes to fix both issues:
* Make execute method clean password in exception
* Make sure mask_password works properly

This backport is not trivial as these fixes relies on many other
changes, only the necessary code have been imported/adapted.

------------------------------------------------
The sync pulls in the following changes (newest to oldest):

63c99a0f - Mask passwords in exceptions and error messages
66142c34 - Make strutils.mask_password more secure
d6b55fb2 - Remove `processutils` dependency on `log`
cb5a804b - Move `mask_password` to strutils

-----------------------------------------------

Closes-Bug: 1343604
Closes-Bug: 1345233
SecurityImpact

Change-Id: I3b49b1d667f6ade9ae3f6765d735440a3e838917
